<SECOND>AM-Crane Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0753,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brother Says Operator in Crane Collapse had Drinking Problem</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 14th, ``All of ..., to UPDATE with report
of drug tests.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The operator of a crane that collapsed and killed five people said he was considering entering an alcohol treatment program to `` dry out'' after his work on the high-rise was over, his brother said Thursday. The crane operator, <PERSON> Lonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>, was among those killed in Tuesday's accident. He had twice tried to commit suicide during the last nine months and had been hospitalized for psychiatric observation twice since March, according to court documents obtained by <ORGANIZATION> McClatchy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>, 45, died with three other construction workers and a school bus driver when the 240-ton crane he was operating plunged 16 floors in the bustling Financial District. <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>' brother, <PERSON> John </PERSON>, said the machine operator had a drinking problem and suffered from stress related to his high-risk job. `` He told me he was considering admitting himself to an alcohol program to dry out after this job was over,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> coroner's office said Thursday that an autopsy would attempt to determine <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>' blood-alcohol level at the time of death. It will be made public in two to three weeks, the coroner's office said. Family members were also `` concerned about, perhaps, a heart problem or stroke,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON> said from his home in <LOCATION> Exeter </LOCATION>, a small city in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. But he conceded he had no specific information that his sibling, a heavy smoker, had a heart condition. `` We mostly were concerned about high cholesterol,'' said <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>, a sales executive. He attributed his brother's problems to `` a bitter divorce and the stress of a high-risk job.'' Authorities were checking into reports that <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON> was seen slumped over the controls as the crane began its plunge. `` We're waiting for the coroner's report to find out whether there may have been a heart attack or something like that, because we have heard _ they are unconfirmed reports _ that someone saw him slumped over,'' said District Attorney <PERSON> Arlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` We're trying to find that individual, if there is somebody, who reported seeing that.'' <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>' sister, 34-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Genoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hefke </ORGANIZATION>, said she spoke Wednesday afternoon with a worker who was on the ground and in radio contact with <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON> before the accident. She said the worker told her that the radio suddenly went silent and that <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON> may have had a heart attack. `` All of a sudden he stopped answering, and then it started rocking back and forth,'' she said. The state <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, said it is investigating reports of illegal drug use among workers at the construction job site, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Friday editions. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fairburn </PERSON>, the agency's deputy director, said <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> would conduct toxicological tests on the bodies of <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON> and three other workers who died, the Times reported. <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON> was in the crane's cab 200 feet above the ground when the accident occurred. The crane was being raised from the 16th floor to the 20th floor of a high-rise under construction for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. The reports of <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>' alcoholism and suicide attempts appeared in Thursday's editions of The Sacramento Bee and The Morning News Tribune of <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON> lived. <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>' employer, the <ORGANIZATION> Erection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Kirkland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, refused to comment. Officials at <ORGANIZATION> Swinerton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Walberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the general contractor for the high-rise project, `` had no knowledge of his personal life,'' said company spokesman <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Duggan </PERSON>. The contractor said the accident apparently was triggered when the head of the crane accidentally rotated 180 degrees while the crane's height was being increased, an operation that requires the machine to be perfectly balanced. However, it said in a statement that the rotation occurred `` for unknown reasons.'' State officials say they are focusing on mechanical or human error, giving `` low priority to such factors as wind or structural failure,'' said <LOCATION> Hamilton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fairburn </LOCATION>, deputy chief of the state <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
