<HEAD>Prominent Singer Allowed to Return to Perform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a sign of further liberalization, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> says it will allow dissident songwriter and singer <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Biermann </PERSON> to perform in the country for the first time since his 1976 expulsion. The official news agency <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION> said Wednsday that <PERSON> Biermann </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, would give performances in <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> on Friday and Saturday. Culture Minister <PERSON> Dietmar </PERSON> <PERSON> Keller </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biermann </ORGANIZATION>'s visit had been approved `` at the wish of many East German artists.'' <PERSON> Biermann </PERSON> was stripped of his East German citizenship and banned from returning home after making critical remarks about the country's Communist government during a tour of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. He was allowed to make a three-day trip to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in 1982 to visit a dying friend. As recently as Nov. 4, East German authorities had prevented <PERSON> Biermann </PERSON> from attending a huge demonstration in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, turning him back from the border. <PERSON> Biermann </PERSON> became a symbolic figure for <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s dissident artists, many of whom emigrated to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> following his expulsion.
