 A southern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> company will barter $ 94 million worth of clothes, electrical goods and daily necessities for six medium-range Soviet passenger jets, an official newspaper said today. The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a collectively owned company based in the special economic zone of <LOCATION> Hainan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, would soon sign the agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Export </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. It quoted the Chinese company's president as saying the three Tupolev-154 and three Yak-42 planes would be sold to local airlines in <LOCATION> Jiangsu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fujian </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> provinces. The report said there was real potential for such deals since both countries are short of hard currency. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would be able to supply consumer goods _ piling up due to a domestic economic slowdown _ to a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> plagued by chronic shortages of such products.
