<FIRST>r w PM-Summit-Baltics     11-30 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Baltics,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lithuanian Leader Seeks US Intercession With Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the people's front of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> says he expects President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to ask <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> for guarantees not to use force against peaceful independence movements in the Baltic republic. `` We have the right to be an independent state,'' <PERSON> Vytautas </PERSON> <PERSON> Landsbergis </PERSON>, chairman of the people's front, or <ORGANIZATION> Sajudis </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday. He said he asked <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policymakers to seek a commitment that the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> security police will not crack down on secessionist movements in <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> or the neighboring republics of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>. `` My information is that they will'' seek such a commitment, said <PERSON> Landsbergis </PERSON>, who met Wednesday with <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Seitz </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> Affairs. <PERSON> Landsbergis </PERSON>, in an interview with <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> editors and reporters, declined to disclose details of his discussions with <PERSON> Seitz </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have not specified what <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will tell <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> when he meets with him in this weekend's shipboard summit off the coast of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Landsbergis </PERSON>, a 57-year-old musicologist, praised the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for refusing to recognize the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s forced annexation of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> at the end of World War II. The Soviet parliament this week passed legislation to give the Baltic republics a large degree of economic autonomy from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, a significant step toward independence. `` The recent legislation should mean we will be able to be less attached to the colonial -LRB- centrally planned Soviet -RRB- system, and should have more room to maneuver,'' he said. Last March, in the most democratic elections in Soviet history, <ORGANIZATION> Sajudis </ORGANIZATION> candidates won 36 of 42 seats allocated to <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> in the national <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Landsbergis </PERSON> predicted that <PERSON> Sajudis </PERSON> would win a majority in elections scheduled for February for the Lithuanian parliament, which he said would then negotiate for independence from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` But <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> might not hear our declaration,'' he said. Therefore, <PERSON> Landsbergis </PERSON> said he asked <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials to seek guarantees of non-intervention and to raise the issue at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> or another international forum. `` We have received support from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for decades in that it has refused to recognize the legality of Soviet annexation. And that has had great importance to us,'' he said. `` Now that the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> issue has become a matter of international importance, we would like <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy to become even more active. `` We would like the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> occupation to be raised at the <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> summit as an international issue that has not been resolved,'' he said. `` Soviet efforts to portray the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> issue as an internal affair have failed.'' <PERSON> Sajudis </PERSON>' immediate goals, he said, are to `` have a pluralistic, multi-party system, and in conjunction with that, to eliminate the monopoly by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the privileges that go with it.'' `` The object is to re-establish sovereignty not only as an expression of our own legitimate right, but because we feel that it is useful for <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in general and also very useful for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` We already have that which we would call spiritual independence. Our people have lost their fear and openly speak their minds,'' <PERSON> Landsbergis </PERSON> said. Asked whether a sovereign <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> would join the Kremlin-led <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> military alliance, <PERSON> Landsbergis </PERSON> said, `` It is possible that it will be a condition for gaining our independence.'' Soviet and Lithuanian negotiators will sit down at a bargaining table in the foreseeable future to hammer out details of Lithuanian independence, he predicted, `` and it may well be that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> will make entry into the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact one of the conditions.''
