<HEAD>Superpower Summit Security Huge Task for Tiny Nation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Providing security for the superpower summit is a huge task for this tiny country, which will dedicate its entire military and most of its police to protecting the American and Soviet presidents. The shipboard location of this weekend's summit between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Marsaxlokk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> has added to security problems and stretched Maltese resources, one official said. But Prime Minister <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenech </PERSON> <PERSON> Adami </PERSON> and others say no special security problems are posed by <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, which is about 220 miles north of <LOCATION> Marsaxlokk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, or by the ability of Libyans to travel freely here. Maltese officials say they are confident their 1,200-member armed forces and 1,800-member police force can protect the leaders during their three-day stay. `` I think our police forces and armed forces are equipped enough and trained enough to provide the necessary security,'' <PERSON> Fenech </PERSON> <PERSON> Adami </PERSON> said in an interview Wednesday. `` Being a small country does not mean that security problems are larger,'' he said. `` In fact, on the contrary, being a small country, both as to the size of the country itself and the size of the population, can render security less of a problem.'' <PERSON> Fenech </PERSON> <PERSON> Adami </PERSON>, who met with Libyan Col. <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> on Sunday in <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> is in favor of the summit and objects only to it being held on warships in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. `` I see no special security threat,'' said armed forces commander Brig. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Spiteri </PERSON>. `` We've always had good relations with the Libyans. ... They have never given us any trouble and there is no reason to suppose they will this time. `` We have n't identified a serious threat from anybody,'' said <PERSON> Spiteri </PERSON>, who commands the security operation. `` But, of course, that can make security concerns more difficult.'' <PERSON> Spiteri </PERSON> said that if there were a specific threat against either <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> or <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> during the summit meetings Saturday and Sunday, authorities could look for it and plan accordingly. One senior government official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said holding the summit aboard the guided missile cruiser USS Belknap and the Soviet missile cruiser <PERSON> Slava </PERSON> had added to security concerns. `` If the summit was only on land, you have just one restricted area to close off,'' the official said. `` But since the leaders will be moving on the island and staying on the ships, we will have to close off areas both on the land and the water.'' He said the government will close the port to commercial traffic _ other than small fishing vessels _ for the three days the leaders are in <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, and close the air space above the harbor to private aircraft. For security reasons, the government has stopped work on a construction project inside the harbor that employed 800 workers, who still will be paid. <PERSON> Spiteri </PERSON> said one Maltese boat will patrol outside the entrance to the harbor and another around the two warships anchored in the center, keeping all pleasure craft and fishing boats at least 200 or 300 meters away from the cruisers. Soldiers will patrol the shoreline and seal off an area near the St. Luciano Tower, a 16th century watch tower built by the Knights of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> on a jagged cliff that juts out into the harbor at the point closest to the warships. Police plan to set up roadblocks and checkpoints near the harbor and close off some roads to the public. The security force will include <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>'s entire military force and most of its police, including an anti-terrorist squad of about 100 members. A source who spoke on condition of anonymity said the three-day security operation is expected to cost the government the equivalent of $ 150,000 in overtime costs, plus at least $ 400,000 from the closing of the harbor and <ORGANIZATION> Malta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freeport </ORGANIZATION> and from stopping construction on the terminal. `` We assume the Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> governments obviously will cover the commercial costs and expenses,'' said the source. `` We do not expect that the two superpowers will expect a small country like <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> to bear the costs of a superpower summit.''
