<HEAD>Some Farmers Getting Around Subsidy Limits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s watchdog agency says some large farming operations are successfully using highly complex methods to get around federal limits on crop subsidies. Despite recent reforms ordered by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, these farming operations have been able to dodge a $ 50,000 limit on federal crop subsidies and probably will continue collecting the fat subsidies again this year. The department's Office of Inspector General said 1987 legislation failed to effectively limit the use of `` multiple legal entities'' to avoid the payment curbs. Other loopholes were also cited. A new audit report released to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday included an example of how the curbs are circumvented: One operation reviewed by auditors in <LOCATION> Tunica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, created 51 irrevocable trusts in 1989 so as not to have payments reduced by further restrictions taking effect this year. The remodeled operation involved three joint ventures controlled by two intermingled families, which had included 43 `` persons'' in 1988. Auditors said the 43 `` persons'' consisted of six individuals and 37 corporations. Owners of the 37 corporations consisted of 11 individuals and one corporation. `` Seven of the individual owners were the immediate members of the two families -LRB- a father and two daughters, and a father, two sons and a daughter -RRB- that controlled the operation,'' the report said. If the complex arrangement had remained as it was in 1988, it would have collected no more than $ 700,000 in payments in 1989. But with reorganization, the operation is expected to collect as much as $ 1,431,576 in subsidies this year. `` One of the family members of this organization told us that the main purpose of the reorganization was to maintain the maximum program benefits,'' the report said. `` He said it became a challenge to see if he could get a trust established for all of the operation's full-time employees. He called it a profit-sharing plan.'' Although the reorganization was allowed by current regulations, auditors said the trusts are believed to be `` flow-through entities'' to avoid new regulations last year limiting a person's membership in more than three entities `` We conclude this because about $ 1.3 billion per year will be routed back to the seven immediate family members through management fees, equipment and land leases, and loans,'' the report said. The heart of the crop subsidies are federal `` deficiency'' payments used to make up part of the difference between a higher target level and a lower market price are supposed to be limited to $ 50,000 per person. As an example, last month's average corn price at the farm was $ 2.20 per bushel. The target price for 1989 corn is $ 2.84. `` However, our review determined that producers have found new, innovative ways to reorganize farming operations so that 1989 payments will not be limited significantly by the legislative changes,'' the report said. The audit report followed one sent to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> describing the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> inspector general's activities for the six-month period that ended Sept. 30. In that review, the excessive crop subsidies were noted among a number of abuses checked by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> investigators and auditors. The audit report released Wednesday dealt specifically with operations of crop programs handled by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The auditors checked five state offices of the agency and 14 county offices. In the counties, 822 of 7,424 farm operating plans were selected for preliminary review. Finally, 52 farms were chosen for in-depth analysis. No individual names were released. States and counties selected for in-depth review included: <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Crittenden </PERSON> and <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> counties; <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>: Butte and Kern; <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>: <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Natchitoches </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tensas </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>: <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Soto </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Noxubee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tunica </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>. The review of 52 farming operations identified 12 that reorganized so that all entities _ which can be individuals, corporation, association, trust or other legal entities _ could continue receiving payments as `` persons'' under the program.
