<HEAD>Ethics Committee Lawyer Denies High-Expense Lobbying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note that some readers might find language in last graf offensive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> lawyer who investigated the ethics case of former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> is rejecting a report that he unfairly lobbied <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> members by taking them to expensive <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> restaurants. A new book on <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s tenure as speaker, `` The Ambition and the Power,'' contends that <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> `` routinely took committee members out to dinner at some of the most expensive restaurants in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'' as part of a calculated campaign to win his case. The book by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> free-lance writer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, published this month by <PERSON> Viking </PERSON>, contends <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> ran up a $ 150,000 expense account while seeking to curry favor with what amounted to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s jury `` That is absolutely nonsense,'' said <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON>, who is running for president of the <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, the top elective post in the county that includes <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. He said he did take several committee members out to lunch and dinner, but when he did, `` it was cheapsville'' _ the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> dining room or a low-priced <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> restaurant. The $ 150,000 figure represented food, lodging and other expenses for a staff of 10 people over a seven-month period, he said. `` The idea that some lawyer from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> could come out and schmooze 12 hard-nosed congressmen into bulldozing the speaker of the House ... defies any kind of logic at all,'' <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, during the two years he spent working on the book, was granted unusually broad access to otherwise private meetings of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leadership and meetings with staff and other lawmakers. He also obtained access to some transcripts from closed-door meetings of the ethics panel. In June, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> became the first speaker in history to resign under fire in mid-term after the ethics panel formally charged him with 69 violations of House rules. How much <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON>'s lobbying of the ethics committee affected the outcome of the case will remain in dispute. Detailed expense records for <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON>'s investigation are not available to the public. The records are kept by a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee chaired by Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaydos </PERSON>, D-Pa., who also is a member of the ethics committee Despite its sympathy with <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s plight before the ethics committee, the book concludes that the former speaker's downfall was largely the result of his own arrogance. House Republicans had long complained about his heavy-handed way of running the chamber, and they believed he overreached to take control of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> policy from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. By the time his ethics problems cropped up <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> had become a lonely figure, estranged even from his own power base among Democrats. The book contrasts what it calls <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON>'s conscious strategy of playing to the political side of the committee with what it portrays as a weak and inept defense of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> by his lawyer, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON>. <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON> appeared not to recognize that committee members were worried about justifying their decision on <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> to the public and the news media, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> writes. <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON> once angrily quoted <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> as having told him, `` This case will be decided by the editorial pages of the nation's newspapers,'' according to the book <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, while contending that he never broke <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules, also seemed to believe that the rules should n't apply to him, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> concludes. A former close aide, <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Raupe </PERSON>, once said, `` I do n't understand how <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> can be so politically in tune and then be almost totally blind to appearances,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> writes The book also contains glimpses inside the sometimes profane and rough world of leadership meetings. At one, members were discussing whether to assign a member who is Jewish to the Foreign Affairs Committee. Ways and <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., objected `` You ca n't put him there. There are already four kikes on that committee,'' he is quoted as saying. A <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> spokesman denied the statement was ever made, but <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said he was certain of the remark.
