<HEAD>Government Needs More Muscle in Substandard Medicare Care: Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee say the government needs more disciplinary muscle against doctors and hospitals that provide substandard care for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> patients. The recommendation was in a report Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that also criticized the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> for a four-year delay in writing regulations to implement a law that gives the agency more power to punish health-care providers. The law, enacted in 1985, allows <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> to deny payment to hospitals and physicians in cases where substandard care is provided. The department is working on the regulations, said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Siebert </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. That agency handles <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>, the government health care program for 33 million elderly, blind and disabled Americans. `` They're fairly controversial and complex regulations,'' he said. `` We've spent a lot of time consulting with medical care industry.'' Physicians may be terminated from participating in Medicare or fined up to the amount of the care provided, but only in cases where there has been a clear pattern of incompetence by physicians who were `` unwilling or unable'' to improve their treatment. The report said the standard that must be met is too stringent because it allows physicians to escape punishment by agreeing to take an educational course to indicate their willingness to improve. It also said the monetary penalty is too low. HHS Inspector General <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON> has recommended that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> strengthen the standard and raise the fine to $ 10,000 per case. The report, based on a three-year investigation by the panel's Human Resources and <ORGANIZATION> Intergovernmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION>, estimated that more than 800,000 errors are made each year by doctors and hospitals caring for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> patients The most common error was not having adequate discharge plans for post-hospital care, the report said. That was the case for about 3 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> admissions selected randomly and reviewed by peer review organizations in 1989, the report said. Extrapolating that to the 11 million annual Medicare admissions amounts to 330,000 failures. `` The large number of beneficiaries who may be at risk of inadequate hospital-discharge planning is of special concern to the committee due to fears that the <ORGANIZATION> PPS </ORGANIZATION> system -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>'s system for paying hospitals -RRB- ... is resulting in patients being discharged faster and less stable,'' the report said. Eight Republicans on the 39-member committee cautioned in an accompanying document that the error estimate was derived by extrapolating from reviews, called generic screens, that are designed to detect potential problems. An error can result from merely failing to sign a form in the proper place, they said. `` If an exhaustive look were taken at all generic screen failures, we are convinced the number of quality problems would be far below the committee report's projections,'' they said. Under the <ORGANIZATION> PPS </ORGANIZATION> system, or prospective payment system created in 1983 as a <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> cost-saving measure, hospitals are paid a flat fee for each treatment they provide. The fee assumes a certain length of hospital stay and medical services.
