<HEAD>Pentagon Estimates $1.7 Billion Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Pentagon estimates it will be forced to slash about $ 1.7 billion from its planned 1990 spending because of the effect of the Gramm-Rudman budget reduction law. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said Wednesday it was n't immediately clear what the exact impact of the cuts would be, or how they would affect manpower decisions <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> called the figure a `` preliminary estimate'' pending formal notification from the Office of Management and Budget. `` We're still trying to figure out how it's all going to fall,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. Had the terms of the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law been fully enforced over a year, defense programs would have been pared by $ 8 billion, or half the $ 16 billion spending reductions the law would have automatically imposed on most federal programs. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said repeatedly in recent weeks that he preferred retaining the across-the-board cuts for a full year to accepting congressional efforts to reduce the deficit, which he said contained phony savings. Pentagon officials had warned of severe cutbacks in military personnel and weapons acquisition if the Gramm-Rudman cuts had been left in place the entire year. The development comes as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> signed, with reservations, a bill authorizing $ 305 billion for defense programs for the current fiscal year, including a cut in his request for the Strategic Defense Initiative. The measure cuts $ 1.1 billion from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s $ 4.9 billion request for spending on the SDI program, or Star Wars, in the fiscal year that began Oct. 1. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in a statement that the measure would provide sufficient funds to `` provide a national defense sufficient to meet foreseeable threats to the national security'' in the coming year. The legislation represents the first cut in the SDI program in six years. The bill also trimmed his request for other major strategic programs such as the MX and Midgetman nuclear missiles and the B-2 stealth bomber. The legislation reduces the ceiling on the number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops overseas by about 15,000. Those troops were associated with intermediate-range nuclear weapons, banned by a U.S.-Soviet treaty signed in December 1988.
