<HEAD>Mulroney Says Gorbachev Deserves Help from the West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Canadian Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, fresh from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, says Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is n't looking for miracles from <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, but deserves help from the West such as observer status at world trade talks President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> had a private dinner at the White House Wednesday night in the last of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s pre-summit consultations with leaders of the Western alliance before he leaves today for <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> and this weekend's shipboard talks with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, who returned Sunday from his own talks with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, spent nearly three hours at the White House before flying back to <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> thanked him profusely for coming. `` I ca n't tell you how much I appreciate your advice and your observations,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Then, in what the president acknowledged was `` a little unorthodox'' fashion, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> left his guest on the driveway to hold forth for Canadian and American reporters. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> defended <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> against charges that he has been too timid in responding to the fast-moving tide of democratic and economic changes sweeping the East Bloc nations. `` The administration has a responsibility to act with prudence,'' he said. `` President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and leader of the Western alliance, and it is important that he act not in haste, but that he act effectively. `` I believe that his intensive preparations and his very constructive attitude, I believe that this is going to bring about good results.'' <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said he recommended that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> be granted observer status at the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade talks _ the discussions where the world's major industrialized nations lay the ground rules for international trade _ and that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> get a personal briefing after each economic summit of the seven major nations of the West. That briefing, he said, should be conducted by the chairman and host of the <ORGANIZATION> G-7 </ORGANIZATION> summit, which happens to be <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for the 1990 meeting to be held next spring or summer in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` What did President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> think of it? I think he kind of liked it,'' said <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>. `` My belief is that President <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> looks upon the <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> summit not with a view to any achieving any miracles, but with a view to building a sustained and solid relationship with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> that will give rise to major accomplishments down the road,'' <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said, is `` in for the long haul himself. I think he's got an ambitious, progressive agenda for the future. `` Some of his suggestions are worthy of thoughtful and generous response, and on the basis of that, there are some gestures that can be taken,'' he said. There also `` might be a series of steps to bring -LRB- the Soviets -RRB- more closely into the INF and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> ambit,'' the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> leader suggested. The meeting was the fourth one-on-one session this year between the two North American leaders. Also attending the private dinner were: Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>; <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Chief of Staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>; <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON>, the national security adviser; <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON>, deputy national security adviser; and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ney </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> was accompanied by Canadian Secretary of State for External Affairs <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>; <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartt </PERSON>, the prime minister's chief of staff; and <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Burney </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> conferred with <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> at Camp David, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, last Friday, and has spoken with other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and Western alliance leaders by telephone in advance of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> summit. He has promised not to spring any surprises on the allies. Asked if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had assured him of no surprises such as former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s discussing abandoning nuclear arms with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Reykavik </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, in 1987, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said, `` Oh, you can be certain of that.''
