<HEAD>New Postage Stamps and Envelopes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, already testing a self-adhesive stamp, is about to try marketing a plastic stamp and a hologram. The self-adhesive 25-cent stamps, showing an eagle and selling for slightly more than face value, are being tested in 15 cities. Early sales have been reported good. The plastic stamp, also self-adhesive, was unveiled this week at World Stamp Expo here and will be test-marketed in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. It was designed to be sold in bank automatic cash machines, and is made of plastic to make it easier for the machines to dispense. A 25-cent stamp, the plastic model features a stylized American flag, with a dozen stamps sold together on a backing sheet the size of a dollar bill. Testing will begin early next year. The hologram, a specialized design in which the image changes color when viewed from different angles, goes on sale Sunday. It is on a stamped envelopes and features a picture of the planned space station. The stamped envelope will cost 30 cents, including the 25 cents postage.
</TEXT>
