<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Machinist union leaders are vowing to continue their strike against <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. Machinists President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kourpias </PERSON> said Wednesday that the union would try to pressure <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company, and the bankruptcy court overseeing the cash-strapped carrier into a settlement. The union also plans to push Eastern to make overdue payments to its pension plan, which is owed as much as $ 1 billion, and take legal action against <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> if the payments are not made. Eastern is strapped for cash and court actions involving the underfunded pension plan could affect <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s attempt to emerge soon from bankruptcy. <PERSON> Kourpias </PERSON> said the union would lobby <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to win enough support to override President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s veto of legislation creating a congressional panel to recommend a solution. Eastern pilots and flight attendants cited the veto last week in deciding to end sympathy strikes in support of the machinists, who walked off the job March 4 after refusing to grant more than $ 150 million in work-rule and other concessions. The union represents more than 3,000 Eastern employees who worked as mechanics and baggage handlers.
