<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In his spacious apartment, <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON> reflected on the price of fleeing West: more than two years' separation from his wife and two sons, starting over in his 40s, and an enduring sense of isolation `` But I'd do exactly the same again. I do n't regret not waiting,'' said <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION>. `` We won three years.'' The pediatrician left <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> illegally in 1986, never expecting the Communist government would permit freedom of travel in his lifetime. `` Now I feel a tremendous pride that I did what I did. It was like moving a mountain with a shovel,'' <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> was among the East Germans who managed to escape before last summer, when neighboring Hungrary opened its borders and released a flood of East Germans to the West. On Nov. 9, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leaders gave up, scrapped travel restrictions and opened the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall. Among the new Westerners, many are young and hopeful, but some are disillusioned. Others, like <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION>, 44, simply are determined to adapt, buoyed daily by the memory of their desperation to leave <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` I do n't think that anybody who has never lived there could ever understand,'' <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON> said. `` I did not want my children to wind up in their 40s in the situation we were in. It was like being a marionette, constantly manipulated.'' Despite the changes, including an amnesty for illegal emigrants declared in October, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> has no intention of going back and has not visited. He believes his children, now 14 and 16, have better opportunities in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. For two 23-year-old <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> secretaries who ducked out of a vacationing group in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and reached <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> in October, life in the West consists of sharing a room in a refugee center with three other women. They have never used computers and have little prospect of finding work or housing. In January, they are due to start a retraining course. `` It's disappointing,'' said one, <PERSON> Kirsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Senger </PERSON>, who left with her best friend, <PERSON> Katrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>. `` But if you want to succeed here, it's possible to fight your way through. On the other side, whatever you did, somebody always closed a door.'' `` If we'd known what was going to happen, I suppose we'd have waited,'' Miss <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>. `` But we'd have been the first through the wall on Nov. 9.'' Miss <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> went home to visit <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> soon after the wall opened, and Miss <PERSON> Senger </PERSON> also plans a visit soon. `` It was good to see my mother, because leaving her without telling her I was going was the saddest thing I've ever known,'' said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>. Even with the hardships of adapting to their new lives, neither wants to give up. `` There was no hope'' in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, and authorities made promises they did not keep, said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>. After repeated applications, <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON>, who worked at a hospital in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> an der <PERSON> Oder </PERSON> along the border with <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, got a five-day exit visa in 1986 to visit relatives in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, 50 miles away. His wife, <PERSON> Sabine </PERSON>, a neurologist, and their sons were not allowed to accompany him. The couple agreed that <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON> would not return. Knowing their telephone would be tapped and mail opened, Mrs. <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON> feigned amazement when her husband pretended to break the news in a telephone call. Secret police raided her apartment. She was fined 20,000 East German marks _ more than 10 times <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON>'s annual salary. Officials decided on the sum as representing half the state-assessed value of their property. Repeatedly, Mrs. <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON> was refused permission to leave. `` They were granting some applications, but highly skilled people had no chance,'' said <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION>. `` There were times when I thought it was hopeless. I promised her if things got too bad, I'd go back even if it meant a year in jail. Suddenly, on Dec. 28, 1988, Mrs. <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON> was told she could go that day. `` I just picked up the children, two suitcases and went,'' she said. In <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> had a relatively good living standard _ an apartment at a nominal rent, a car and more money than there were goods to buy. Their skills were in desperately short supply, while <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has a surplus of doctors. Some 1,200 doctors are out of work in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> alone, with numbers being swelled by emigres from the east. <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION>, a senior consultant in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, got a job as an assistant consultant at <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Neukoelln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. It pays 5,500 West German marks, nearly $ 3,000 a month after taxes. He lived in a small apartment in the nurses' quarters, saving for the arrival of his family. They now live in their own apartment, which rents for $ 973 a month. Mrs. <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON> considers herself lucky to have found a job _ she works assessing accident victims' disabilities for an insurance group _ and both speak with distaste of what they see as a mercenary attitude of many of their West German colleagues. Mrs. <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON> said some had suggested she should feel guilty about leaving patients behind in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` They have no place to talk to me about feeling guilty,'' she said. `` Here we see them cheating patients by giving them unnecessary treatment.'' Her husband cited instances when, he said, doctors `` see a patient four or five times when one or two appointments would do.'
