<FIRST>r a PM-Hepatitis Bjt   11-30 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hepatitis, Bjt,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interferon First Treatment for Hepatitis C</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Injections of the natural disease-fighting protein interferon give doctors their first effective weapon against hepatitis C, a virus that infects at least 150,000 Americans annually, according to a report today. `` In my opinion, this is a major clinical advance,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION>. The work appears to represent another milestone in a year of advances against this elusive virus. Until recently, doctors were sure of only two hepatitis viruses, type A and type B. Since many people got hepatitis without exposure to these viruses, their disease was simply labeled non-A, non-B. In April, researchers from <ORGANIZATION> Chiron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Emeryville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, reported the discovery of a new hepatitis virus, which they called hepatitis C. They said it is the principal culprit in non-A, non-B hepatitis. They also described a new test that will reveal whether blood is tainted with the virus. Hepatitis C is the most common serious infection that is passed through blood. Perhaps 5 percent of all Americans who get routine transfusions become infected, although estimates vary widely. However, this hazard should largely disappear soon when the new screening test for the virus becomes available, perhaps next year. Most cases of hepatitis C are mild. About half those infected become long-term carriers, and 10 percent suffer cirrhosis of the liver. The latest research, involving 207 people, shows that therapy with alpha interferon, a human protein produced through genetic engineering, can temporarily shut down the virus' attack. The treatment stopped the destruction of liver cells in about half of those with chronic disease. However, in more than half of those who are helped, the disease returned when treatment ended. Researchers hope that giving interferon for longer period or in higher doses will hold the virus in check or wipe it out. `` This is a very common disease,'' said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. `` There has been nothing available for these people in the past. While this controls the disease rather than cures it, it is the first therapeutic intervention that has been offered these people.'' `` It looks promising that anti-viral treatment will be useful in this disease,'' added Dr. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoofnagle </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diabetes </ORGANIZATION> and Digestive and Kidney Diseases. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hoofnagle </PERSON> were co-authors of separate studies that reached similar conclusions about interferon's effectiveness. Both were published in the New England Journal of Medicine. Hepatitis B is spread mainly through blood and sexual contact and is a major underlying cause of cirrhosis and liver cancer. Blood banks also test donations for hepatitis A, which usually spreads through contaminated food and water. While it can cause serious illness, people do not get lingering infections with hepatitis A. `` Hepatitis C virus is a vastly more common problem than HIV -LRB- the AIDS virus -RRB- and considerably more common than hepatitis B, for which we have been testing for 20 years. It's the most common serious virus infection'' passed through transfusions, said Dr. <PERSON> Lewellys </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON>, head of blood services at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In another report in the journal, <ORGANIZATION> Chiron </ORGANIZATION> scientists teamed with researchers from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transfusion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> to strengthen the case that hepatitis C is the major, and possibly the only, cause of non-A, non-B hepatitis. They tested 15 people who got non-A, non-B hepatitis through transfusions and found that all were infected with hepatitis C. Donors were also infected with this virus. Just how many Americans get hepatitis C each year is unclear. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> estimates that about 150,000 of the 3 million Americans who get transfusions annually become infected. However, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> uses a far lower estimate. In an editorial in the journal, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s Dr. <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. Alter estimated that a total of 150,000 Americans get hepatitis C each year from all causes. Among these are 7,500 to 15,000 who catch it through transfusions. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> estimates that 40 percent get the infection through drug abuse. Other sources include on-the-job exposure to blood, sexual intercourse and household contact with infected people. However, in about 40 percent of cases there is no clear explanation of how the infection occurs.
</TEXT>
