<TEXT>
 The rice was bugged, and we're not talking wiretaps. The sesame seeds had a problem, too. So did the apricots, the bean curd and the macaroni. In all, <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> said Wednesday, 15 of 17 imported foods his staff bought in the city and had tested at a private laboratory contained bugs or bug parts. At a City Hall news conference, <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> accused the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> of failing to enforce its food contamination standards. He also said the standards themselves are too low. Most of the foods he had tested _ including 2 ounces of Haitian milled corn with 26 insect fragments in it _ were within allowable federal standards. But six were so badly tainted they violated the limits, <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> said. Among them, he said, were a 5-pound bag of Indian rice containing one live bug _ a red flour beetle _ and 11 whole dead ones, including sawtoothed grain beetles and a rice weevil. There was a dead moth in the Chinese sesame seeds, a rat or mouse hair in the Chinese bean curd preserves and 481 insect fragments in the Greek macaroni. `` Had they been properly inspected, they would have been barred from sale in this country,'' <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> said. He blamed federal budget cuts under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration that reduced the number of <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> inspectors while food imports tripled. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> replied that it spends most of its time looking for food that contains microbiological contamination that could make people sick. Bugs, while unappetizing, generally do not pose a direct health threat, said <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Janiger </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGAN