<HEAD>Federal Judge Rejects Philadelphia Set-Aside</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> school district program that gave preference to minority contractors has been struck down by a federal judge who said it failed to meet a new, more rigid test established by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> on Wednesday said that `` generalized assertions'' of discrimination were not enough to justify the program, which mandates that a minimum percentage of each contract be given to firms controlled by minorities and women. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in January struck down a similar set-aside program in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. Since then, lower courts around the country have overturned other such programs. <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> ruled in a case brought by a white-owned construction firm, <ORGANIZATION> Main </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Devon </LOCATION>, after it lost out on a contract for demolition and asbestos removal at an elementary school. School officials Wednesday had no comment. The set-aside program was established in 1984. The district based its plan, which requires that each contract include at least 15 percent minority and 10 percent female participation, on a general finding of discrimination in awarding of contracts. A <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> investigation showed that only 0.5 percent of district contracts went to minority firms in 1982 and 1983. But <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> wrote that such evidence was not sufficient. `` It is clear that a majority of the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> -RRB- </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANI