<HEAD>Search for Plane Ended, 8 Presumed Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with cabin panel found, NTSB investigator
saying that without wreckage it will be difficult to determine crash's
cause. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NARRAGANSETT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight people aboard a twin-engine commuter plane that vanished off <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> have been given up for dead. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> called off the search by air and sea Wednesday night for the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> plane that disappeared Tuesday during a 17-mile flight from <LOCATION> Block </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> to the mainland. Searchers had found the bodies of a passenger's two dogs that had been on board, as well as a cabin panel, life jackets, seat cushions, a headset and other debris believed to be from the plane, but saw no other sign of the aircraft itself or those aboard. `` The results of the search indicated there were probably no survivors from the crash,'' Petty Officer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jersey </PERSON> said. In Westerly, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> said today that without wreckage the cause of the crash is unlikely to be determined. `` I think all we're going to be able to do today is go through the aircraft records and the pilot records, and unless something comes up out of the ordinary, there wo n't be much,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> had no authority to order a search for the wreckage, and any attempts to find it would be up to the airline's insurance company, <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> began its search shortly after the British <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Islander </PERSON> plane, built in 1969, was reported missing. Coast Guard officials had expressed hope early Wednesday of finding survivors, but veteran islanders said the seas of 5 to 6 feet and water temperature of about 45 degrees made survival unlikely. The debris was found mainly in an area where the water averages 100 feet deep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Grady </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' attorney, said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> would also investigate. The plane `` had the most thorough inspection it gets in the preceding 30 days,'' he said.
