<HEAD>Government to Begin Dismantling Fortifications on Austrian Border</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with today's events. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said today it will begin dismantling its fortifications along the border with <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, and lawmakers recommended abolishing some of the toughest laws used to crack down on dissent. Government spokesman <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Jansen </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> was asked today to start immediate removal of `` technical equipment'' along parts of the Czechoslovak-Austrian border. Such equipment includes concrete pylons linked with barbed wire and some electronic wire to detect trespassers. The moves came one day after <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> took the historic step of removing the guaranteed leading role of the Communist Party from the constitution. <PERSON> Jansen </PERSON> refused to specify when and exactly where work on the border would start, saying it was likely to begin near the Slovak capital of <LOCATION> Bratislava </LOCATION>, a one-hour drive east of <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. In May, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> started dismantling fortifications along its border with neutral <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, its only point of contact with a Western country. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> also has a long border with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Jansen </PERSON> made no mention of action along that border. The order to dismantle part of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s portion of the Iron Curtain reflected the new foreign policy that Communist Premier <PERSON> Ladislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON> has promised to follow. <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON> is due to name a new coalition government by Sunday that would include non-Communists and possibly members of the Civic Forum opposition group, which headed up 11 days of anti-government protests and a hugely successful general strike Monday. He continued consultations today after announcing that he could accept opposition suggestions on whom to include. Civic Forum spokesman <PERSON> Jiri </PERSON> <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> said Wednesday night that the opposition wanted a civilian Communist in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and a non-Communist overseeing police forces at the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> reiterated past statements that Civic Forum has no Cabinet aspirations, but he did not specifically exclude participation in the government by some of the experts who have worked with the opposition. Seeking to paint himself as a figure of national consensus in the current crisis, <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON> in a television speech Wednesday made a number of points aimed at winning him the sympathy of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s 15.5 million citizens. His call for a reassessment of the 1968 <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> invasion that crushed the 1968 `` Prague Spring'' reforms was accompanied by a pledge to negotiate the withdrawal of the 80,000 Soviet troops stationed in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Those troops were seen as the legitimizing force of the Czechoslovak leaders installed by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> after the invasion. Those leaders _ ousted party chief <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> and other top Communists _ now have lost power. The state news agency <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> today said unidentified parliamentary deputies suggested abolition of toughened laws on public order, which were passed in March and used to impose stiff fines or jail terms on hundreds of people arrested during a series of anti-government demonstrations in January. The deputies said this amendment, and a series of other new legal measures, should be submitted for consideration in Parliament Dec. 12-13. The deputies also proposed shortening the period of pre-trial custody to a two-month maximum. Political prisoners have sometimes waited more than a year to go to court. The deputies also proposed removing the criminal offense of `` abusing a religious function'' from the statute books. This law, which imposed maximum imprisonment of three years, was frequently used against priests deemed to have overstepped the strict state controls on churches in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Priests must have a state licence to practice in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, and many have had to go underground after being barred from office by the authorities. The deputies also want an unspecified change in the criminal code article on emigration, <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> said. It seemed likely they would seek to drop criminal charges against those who left the country illegally. The deputies also recommended that the independence of courts be anchored in a new draft constitution to be published and passed soon. They also seek a new law meting out punishment to those who damage the environment. Thirty percent of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s forests have been destroyed by acid rain and other pollution, and both air and water are heavily polluted in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and several other cities. Tighter control of pollution by large state enterprises has been a key demand of opposition groups for several years. Also today, six political prisoners were reported released, and former Charter 77 spokesman <PERSON> Stanislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Devaty </PERSON>, who went underground several weeks ago, and another rights activist were amnestied by President <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Husak </PERSON>. There were no other details immediately available.
