<HEAD>Costly 1989 Atlantic Season Ends With Tropical Storm Karen Forming
Near Cuba</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with depression forming into Tropical
Storm Karen, UPDATES total of named storms. PICKS UP 14th graf, `Last year
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN THOMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 1989 hurricane season, marked by the costliest storm in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history, officially ended today with yet another tropical storm forming in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. At 8 a.m. EST, Tropical Storm <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>, with 50 mph winds, was about 125 miles south-southwest of <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> and was not expected to strengthen, said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION>. It was drifttng toward <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> at about 5 mph. Depressions become named storms when their sustained winds reach 39 mph; hurricanes have winds of at least 74 mph. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> is the 11th named storm of the season, which began June 1. The six-month season was far less deadly than 1988's, in which 550 people died in storms. This year's storms killed 84 people, including 56 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said meteorologist <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON>. Hurricane Hugo was blamed for 49 deaths, including 21 in this country. It slammed into <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> on Sept. 21. `` I've seen greater damage in smaller areas,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheets </PERSON>, director of the hurricane center. `` But I've never seen it on such a large scale where you go mile after mile with such massive damage.'' Overall damage from Hugo totaled about $ 10 billion. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, it caused a record storm damage of about $ 7 billion. Most of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> damage was around <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> are racing to recover from Hugo in time for the tourist season. `` We are still in a sense reeling from the effects of <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> but that did n't dampen our spirit,'' said <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrelly </PERSON>, governor of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. He said Wednesday that St. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> and <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> are ready for winter tourists and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Croix </LOCATION> would be ready by early 1990. It was the most expensive disaster for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> since the organization began 110 years ago. Latest figures show the agency has spent about $ 38 million in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caudill </PERSON>, a spokesman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The hurricane season, which began June 1, had four tropical storms, counting <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>, and seven hurricanes. The storms also were stronger than usual, said Sheets. Last year, there were seven tropical storms and five hurricanes. The <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> season usually has 10 named storms. Normally, only five or six whip up the 74-mph sustained winds to become a hurricane. <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>, the fifth major <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane in the last decade to reach <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shores, may have marked the end of a 30-year period of fewer, weaker hurricanes, Sheets said. `` There have been fewer of the stronger hurricanes making landfall since the 1960s,'' Sheets said. `` Now maybe we're starting to return to more normal activity like we had in the'50s and'60s.'' During the 1950s, eight major hurricanes hit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, while seven struck the following decade. After <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>, the most damaging tropical system this year was Tropical Storm <PERSON> Allison </PERSON>. It dumped large amounts of rain and caused 11 deaths and $ 500 million damage in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>.
