<HEAD>Whereabouts of Comaneci Still Unknown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Nadia </PERSON> <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON>, the world renowned gymnast who made Olympic history when she was 14 years old, has dropped from sight after fleeing across the Romanian border into <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON>'s former coach, <PERSON> Bela </PERSON> <PERSON> Karolyi </PERSON>, said today she was `` probably'' in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> obtaining travel papers, but an embassy spokesman denied it. <PERSON> Karolyi </PERSON> became a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen last spring and is currently in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> with an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women's gymnastics team. Ms. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> told Hungarian border officials she had been banned by Romanian leader <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> from traveling abroad and was fleeing her native land `` for the sake of freedom,'' official media reported. Ms. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> crossed into <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> by car before dawn Tuesday at the border town of <LOCATION> Kiszombor </LOCATION>, with six other Romanians who were not identified, the <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. Her defection was a surprise, particularly because the 28-year-old athlete-turned-trainer reportedly had close ties with the <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> family and at one time was said to have been romantically involved with the Romanian president's son, <PERSON> Nicu </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> dropped from sight Wednesday, when she and her companions left the hotel in the nearby town of <LOCATION> Szeged </LOCATION> where they had been lodged by police, according to Hungarian press reports. Ms. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> had been given a three-day temporary residence permit. A spokesman at the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olympic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> today the gymnast had not contacted them and they knew nothing of her whereabouts. Because of her achievements, Ms. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> was named a `` Hero of Socialist Labor'' by <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>, the hard-line leader who declared at last week's <ORGANIZATION> Romanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that he would not yield to the forces of reform sweeping the rest of the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bloc </LOCATION>. At age 14, Ms. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> dazzled the sports world at the 1976 <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> Olympic Games with the first-ever scores of perfect 10s in Olympic gymnastics. She won three gold medals, in the uneven bars, balance beam and overall competitions. The achievements of the 4-foot-11 teen-ager brought her elite status in her homeland and tremendous popularity in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. During a competitive career that lasted until 1984, Ms. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> won a total of 21 gold medals in Olympic and other international contests. She reportedly had been living in an eight-room villa and had a Western car, both extremely rare for private citizens in a country that has endured chronic shortages of consumer goods for most of this decade. In the past two years, tens of thousands of Romanians have sought refuge in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> because of worsening economic conditions and political intransigence at home. `` Just like me, she was chased out of the country by the Romanian authorities,'' said <PERSON> Karolyi </PERSON>, who defected to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1981.
