<HEAD>Policeman Says Motorcyclist Was Aiming For Him</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th pvs, `Lozano's account ...' with cross-examination
of officer. PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, `Lozano was ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A police officer whose slaying of a black suspect set off three days of rioting took the stand at his manslaughter trial today and said he fired because the man was bearing down on him with his motorcycle. `` I turned my body to face the motorcycle. He just came straight at me with a tremendous noise,'' said Officer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON>. `` He was just aiming at me. I was just able to turn my body, draw my gun and shoot.'' The five-year veteran of the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said he thought he was going to die and was briefly in shock. After recovering, he said, he found no vital signs when he checked on the motorcyclist. He saw that the cyclist's passenger was injured and radioed a dispatcher to say he had fired his weapon and a fatality was involved. The prosecution charges <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> acted with gross negligence when he shot and killed the motorcyclist, <PERSON> Clement </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>, 23, on Jan. 16, sparking three days of rioting in the community's black neighborhoods. The passenger, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>, died the next day. <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> is charged with manslaughter in their deaths. <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON>, 31, testified that he was `` hyper'' and that the dispatcher did not understand his first transmission. He said he took a deep breath and repeated it. Within moments, an angry crowd gathered and <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> said he and others `` were getting hit right and left'' with rocks and bottles. <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON>'s account came after a half-hour of questioning about his personal history and his police service, giving the jury an impression of a well-trained officer with a list of commendations. Under cross examination, Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> to read aloud from a police review document that listed <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> as average in most categories, including decision-making and reliability. <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> also had <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> recount an incident in which a jai-alai player accused <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> of physical abuse during a strike. <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> was just beginning to review the events leading up to the shooting when the trial was recessed for 45 minutes after an alternate juror complained of abdominal pain and nausea. Addressing his answers with a slight Spanish accent directly to the jury, the Colombian-born <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> wore a dark blue suit, dress shirt and red tie for his appearance. The testimony was broadcast live on <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> television and radio. Prosecution witnesses contended that the motorcyclist was in the opposite lane from <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> when the officer coolly took aim at the driver, tracked him with his gun and fired the fatal shot as the bike was about to pass him. The defense, however, insists that the motorcyclist, attempting to outrun a pursuing squad car, had crossed into the traffic lane where <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> was standing and the officer shot in self-defense to avoid being run over. One defense witness, 18-year-old <PERSON> Dedrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Belle </PERSON>, balked at giving depositions and had fled investigators attempting to talk to him, according to court testimony. <PERSON> Belle </PERSON>, who lives in the <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION> neighborhood where the shooting and subsequent rioting occurred, told the court Wednesday he feared for his life if he was made to testify for the defense. `` It will result in violence ... because I'm black and he shot a black guy,'' <PERSON> Belle </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Dade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Farina </PERSON>. Over the objections of media attorneys, the judge banned any filming of <LOCATION> Belle </LOCATION> during his brief testimony. His testimony was aimed at compromising star prosecution witness <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, who was talking with <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> just before the shooting. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> wound up with the cartridge casing from the fatal bullet after the shooting, but denied on the stand that he had waved it about or shown it to neighbors before turning it over to police. <PERSON> Belle </PERSON>, however, said <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> showed the shell to everyone, and even let him hold it. Other defense witnesses Wednesday included a former <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> professor, <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Alpert </PERSON>, who prepared a study of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> police weapon discharges between Jan. 1, 1980, and Dec. 31, 1986. <PERSON> Alpert </PERSON>, who now teaches at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>, said 13 percent of the 150 shootings he examined were instances in which an officer was firing while being attacked by a vehicle. The prosecution has contended that <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> disregarded police policy when he failed to step out of the roadway, and then fired at a moving vehicle. When the case opened Oct. 23, the defense attempted unsuccessfully to move the trial, arguing that <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> juries would be too worried about renewed racial violence to find <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> innocent. Twice before in this decade, innocent verdicts favoring policemen accused of killing blacks have led to rioting, and the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Metro-Dade </ORGANIZATION> police forces have been on alert because of <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON>'s trial.
