<HEAD>Don't Close Leaning Tower, Pisa Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PISA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Local officials Thursday disputed the government's plan to close <LOCATION> Pisa </LOCATION>'s famed leaning tower for restoration work, saying it is in no immediate danger. `` The closure is unjustified because the situation of the tower has not worsened recently and because conservation work can be initiated without banning tourists,'' said <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Toniolo </PERSON>, who heads Opera Primaziale, the private institution managing and restoring the tower. An estimated 800,000 visitors a year climb the 294 marble steps of the 162-foot monument, bringing in revenue of about $ 71.4 million. The government commission for public works suggested Tuesday the leaning tower be closed immediately. A final decision by the government is expected soon, although the city can appeal it to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. Government experts are worried because its tilt has been increasing by an average 0.047 inches a year since measurements began in 1918. The tower was completed in 1360, and experts believe it began leaning immediately because it was built on sinking soil. The government has allotted $ 7.1 million for the conservation of the tower, but experts have been stumped on how to save it. <PERSON> Gero </PERSON> <PERSON> Geri </PERSON>, a professor of topography in <LOCATION> Pisa </LOCATION>, has said it will take at least 100 years before the tower reached the point of toppling.
