<HEAD>South Carolina Gets $8.4 million in Federal Money for Fire Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government will give <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> $ 8.4 million to fight the threat of forest fires fueled by thousands of trees downed by Hurricane Hugo, state and federal officials said Thursday. The money will be used to cut 11,400 miles of firebreaks, lease fire detection and fighting equipment, fund a public awareness program and coordinate efforts to salvage downed timber worth an estimated $ 1 billion, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. `` We at <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> believe the Hugo forest blow-down is a serious emergency with the potential for great danger in the event of serious, uncontrolled wildfires,'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. Officials say 36 percent of the 12.2 million acres of forested land in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> was damaged by the Sept. 21 storm. They say they are weighing plans to ban burning in some unincorporated areas of the state to lessen the fire danger.
