 </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Base maintain nuclear missiles and strategic bombers. The <LOCATION> Minot </LOCATION> base opened in 1959, and the Grand Forks base in 1960. The <LOCATION> Minot </LOCATION> base has about 14,000 military personnel and their families, the Grand Forks base 13,000. Both bases contribute more than $ 200 million to the economies of their communities. `` We're disappointed, of course,'' said <LOCATION> Minot </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Christensen </PERSON>. `` We do n't know what they have down the line, but we'd accept anything else. Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Caruana </PERSON>, commander of the Grand Forks base, said construction of the MX system could begin in 1992 and the system could become operational two years later. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> houses about 300 Minuteman missiles _ each capable of carrying three warheads _ in underground silos near <LOCATION> Minot </LOCATION> and Grand Forks. The MX missiles can carry up to 10 warheads. <PERSON> Caruana </PERSON> said the Grand Forks garrison will cost $ 80 million to $ 100 million, and employ as many as 450 people. But Grand Forks Mayor <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Polovitz </PERSON>, along with the state's congressional delegation, cautioned that the project might not be built at all because of changes taking place in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and its Eastern European allies `` I still have some questions whether it will be funded because of what is happening in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> now,'' <PERSON> Polovitz </PERSON> said. `` I'm pleased that we as acommunity got together and worked for this. I'm also pleased with what's happening in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, so we're kind of caught in between. `` If they go ahead with the rail garrison and fund it, I'm pleased as the dickens to have it here in Grand Forks. Peace activists, meanwhile, were unhappy with the entire idea of the MX missiles. `` An MX missile by its very nature is a first-strike weapon,'' said <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Hermodson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Crookston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Crookston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, near Grand Forks. `` I see this either as a continuation of first-strike capability or as a welfare program for weapons manufacturers. I think it's a little of both.''
