<HEAD>The Son of Stavropol Peasants Finds Place for Religion in His Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The man struggling to renew <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>'s revolution more than 70 years after it declared religion the `` opiate of the people'' was himself baptized in his peasant village into the ancient rites of Russian Orthodoxy. And if 58 years later <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> does not believe in God, his early years apparently engendered a healthy respect for those who do, including his mother. The <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> years have seen a dramatic shift in official tolerance of religion in a country whose people ostensibly have been turned into spiritual materialists by decades of Communist dogma. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has told religious leaders that they, too, have a place in the Communist-led healing of the nation's psyche. But as government pressure eases, the future of a nascent religious revival is beginning to depend more on the willingness of church leaders to throw off their own strictures and traditional subservience. Since <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> became Soviet leader in March 1985: _ The number of baptisms and reopenings of churches in the Christian heartland have increased dramatically. Important religious centers like the Pechorsky Monastery of <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> have been given back. Jews also enjoy greater religious freedom and a revival of Islam in Central <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> is increasing the number of seminary students and mosques. _ Scores of religious dissidents of all faiths have been freed from jails and prison camp. _ The patriarch of the Russian Orthodox Church has met with the Soviet leader for the first time in more than 40 years. Clergy celebrated the 400th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Patriarchate on Oct. 13 with the first service in more than 70 years in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Uspensky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cathedral </LOCATION>, where Russian czars once were crowned _ <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has met with a top representative of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, and will meet with Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on Friday. Members of the banned Ukrainian <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in the western <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> believe the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> meeting will lead to legalization of their church after 43 years underground. Asked in July whether he had been baptized after his birth in 1931 in the southern Russian village of <LOCATION> Privolnoye </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> replied: `` Yes, I was. I think it's quite normal, is n't it?'' Reporters who have visited the area say his mother, <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>, still regularly attends Russian Orthodox services. Interviewed by Finnish TV in conjunction with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> in October, Archbishop <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION> said the official attitude toward religion in that region, which includes <LOCATION> Privolnoye </LOCATION>, eased when <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was the local <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader. `` Practically speaking, beginning in 1975 in <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION> churches and groups of believers have been able to exercise all their rights,'' he said. `` We've had perestroika since 1975.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was regional party chief from 1970 to 1978. When he met with Patriarch <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON> of the Russian Orthodox Church prior to the celebration of the church's millenium in 1988, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> made clear that religious believers have both a stake and a place in his reform program. The millenium, he said, should be `` marked by the consolidation of our country's believers, all working people, for the sake of our common great cause of perestroika, of the renewal of socialism, the complete unfolding of its humanistic ethical potential.'' Soviet officials have been reporting for more than two years that a new law on religion is being prepared, and they say it is likely to be presented to the Soviet legislature soon. They promise the law will ease strict Stalin-era prohibitions on group religious instruction and charitable work by churches, and make it easier for them to receive official recognition. The law has not yet been changed, but some Russian Orthodox churches have begun to act. According to the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> parishes are contributing heavily to support children's homes in the capital <PERSON> Veniamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Yefremov </PERSON>, an inspector for the government <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> that has been charged with overseeing believers, encouraged more charitable work. `` Apparently some people are waiting for some instructions from above. There is only one instruction in such work _ the dictates of the heart,'' he said. Muscovites say baptism has become increasingly popular, even fashionable, in some circles. But it does not mean that the baptized know much about the faith they have embraced, or even want to know. Two scholars, writing in the Communist theoretical journal <PERSON> Kommunist </PERSON> in 1987, said people had begun flocking to churches to find some beauty in the religious chanting and church icons that was missing in their increasingly cheerless lives in the Soviet system. Religious critics wonder whether Russian Orthodox Church officials, used to taking what the government is willing to give, can take advantage of the freer atmosphere. During recent harsh years, the Russian Orthodox Church concentrated much activity on disarmament issues, which at the time coincided with Soviet government propaganda efforts. Ukrainian Catholics are demanding the return from the Russian Orthodox Church of buildings and property taken over when their religion was forced underground in 1946. `` If we could count on sincerity and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> love from the Russian church there would n't be a problem,'' said Father <PERSON> Yaroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Chukhny </PERSON>, who led <LOCATION> Lvov </LOCATION>'s Cathedral of the Transfiguration from the Russian Orthodox Church to the Ukrainian <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> on Oct. 29. `` The essence of religion is not building churches or holding beautiful services, but the morals of man,'' he said.
