<TEXT>
 A state legislative committee approved and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> for debate today $ 1.1 billion in tax increases to close the budget deficit that signaled the end of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Miracle. The package of higher taxes on capital gains, sales and gasoline was approved on a voice vote Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. It immediately drew fire from both legislators and the public. `` This bill imposes the most regressive kind of a tax, hitting hardest those in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> who can least afford it,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> was scheduled to begin debate on the package today, and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leaders said they hoped to send it to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by the end of the week. The proposal is the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s latest move to deal with the deficit, which a <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> staffer said had swelled to $ 825 million. Only a year ago, the economic boom dubbed the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Miracle nearly carried Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to the White House. As the committee sent the proposal to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> held hearings on a $ 350 million House-approved package of spending cuts. Legislative leaders envision enacting the cuts in conjuction with the tax package, which has been embraced by the governor. Under the tax package, the sales tax would rise from five cents to seven cents on the dollar; the gas tax would go from 11 cents to 21 cents per gallon, and capital gains would be increased from 5 percent to 7.5 percent. The package would raise nearly $ 1.1 billion in additional revenue by the next fiscal year. Still more revenue would be raised by shifting $ 30 million more in cigarette taxes into the general fund and by collecting $ 24 million in unclaimed returnable-bottle deposits. The package was developed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leadership, and Speaker <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Keverian </PERSON> backed it up by telling several committee chairmen they should resign if they they could not support it. One committee chairman quit on Tuesday. Democratic Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON> spoke up for new taxes before the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> vote, saying it was time the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> and the administration corrected spending errors that were based on overly ambitious revenue estimates. `` At what point do we face up to the fact that we were all wrong about the deficit?'' he asked. Rep. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> minority leader, said the Democratic leadership's deficit estimates are designed to promote taxes. He estimated the deficit is less than $ 500 million and accused the Democratic leadership of `` twisting arms and getting that tax bill through here as quickly as possible.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, said the increase in the capital gains tax would stifle economic growth. `` We are going to ... hurt our image and make ourselves less attractive to investors from outside the state,'' he said.
