<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reduced levels of an important protein molecule may play a role in the collapse of the immune system in patients infected with the AIDS virus, according to a study at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. Dr. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crystal </PERSON>, a researcher at the National Heart, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, one of the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> agencies, said a deficit of glutathione was found in a group patients infected with the AIDS virus and he suggests that this `` may be one clue about why the immune dysfunction occurs'' in victims of the disease. In a study to be published Friday in the British medical journal <ORGANIZATION> Lancet </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Crystal </ORGANIZATION> and seven other researchers report that they measured the levels of glutathione in the blood and lung fluids of 14 patients infected with the AIDS virus and compared the results with studies of 19 patients not infected with AIDS. <PERSON> Crystal </PERSON> said that patients who were `` seropositive,'' or infected with the human immunodeficiency virus -LRB- HIV -RRB- that causes AIDS, had glutathione levels reduced by one-third to one-half of what is normal. `` What we found is that the glutachione level in seropositive people was low, suggesting a systemic deficiency of glutathione,'' said the researcher. The patients in the study infected with HIV had normal levels of lymphocytes, a disease-fighting white blood cell attacked by the AIDS virus, and their disease had not progressed to full-blown AIDS. Crystal said glutathione is a common protein molecule whose precise function in the body is not known, but earlier research has proven that it is important in the body's shield against infection. `` It seems to play an important role in allowing the immune system to function normally,'' said Crystal. `` Nobody knows why or how, but ... the immune system does better when glutathione is around. There's a lot of evidence of that.'' A deficiency of glutathione, he said, may be a clue in a medical mystery that has puzzled AIDS researchers for years. <PERSON> Crystal </PERSON> said that early in the course of an AIDS virus infection, there `` clearly is immune dysfunction,'' but, yet, there typically are very, very few cells that are actually infected with HIV. How the disease could compromise the immune system with so few `` soldiers'' attacking the body's cells has been one of the unanswered questions about AIDS, he said. `` There has got to be ways that the -LRB- HIV -RRB- infection amplifies itself in terms of its effect on the body,'' said Crystal. `` This -LRB- the glutathione deficiency -RRB- may be one clue about why the immune dysfunction occurs.'' The scientist emphasized that finding the exact role that reduced glutathione plays in the course of an AIDS virus infection will require a great deal more research before there could be any clinical application. `` We are evaluating the very important question of whether this glutathione deficiency is relevant ... or does it have nothing to do with -LRB- immune dysfunction -RRB-? That is a possibility,'' said Crystal. AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune system, leaving it unable to resist other infections. HIV, which causes AIDS, is spread most often through sexual relations, through contact with blood or blood products, such as by sharing needles, or from mother to child during the birth process. As of Sept. 30, AIDS had been diagnosed in 109,167 Americans, of whom more than half, or 64,849, have died since June 1, 1981, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
