<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Holocaust     11-30 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Holocaust,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opening of East Bloc May Shed New Light on Holocaust</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Liberalization in the Communist bloc is providing an unexpected opportunity for historians to examine long-hidden documents on <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s extermination of European Jewry. Tens of thousands of documents from <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and others expected from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> may answer such central questions as how many Jews really died, which could be more than the accepted 6 million, researchers said Thursday. Despite four decades of scholarship on the Holocaust, the unavailability of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> accounts has left gaping holes in knowledge about the World War II slaughter, said <PERSON> Shmuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Krakowsky </PERSON>, head archivist at <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s Yad Vashem Holocaust Memorial. The largest mystery has been the fate of Soviet Jews: how many were killed, how they died and where they died. `` We have never been able to compile final figures of how many died. It could be that far fewer succeeded in escaping executions than we imagined,'' <PERSON> Krakowsky </PERSON> said. Himself a survivor of the Lodz Ghetto in wartime <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Krakowsky </PERSON> is in charge of reviewing 50,000 pages of East German documents, about a third of which were brought to <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> this week by archivists from <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. The documents have arrived in advance of a cooperation agreement that Israeli and East German researchers are scheduled to sign Monday. <PERSON> Krakowsky </PERSON> said he scanned some of the information while on a visit to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in 1988. In September, <PERSON> Krakowsky </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Yad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vashem </ORGANIZATION>'s director <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Arad </PERSON> spent three weeks studying thousands of pages of newly available Holocaust documents in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minsk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Odessa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>. The material in the Soviet and German archives suggested new directions in investigating how the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> operated in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Krakowsky </PERSON> said. `` We were astounded to read of documented persecutions, names and places we had n't been aware of,'' he said. `` It adds a lot to our information about the Holocaust. Until now knowledge of the fate of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jewry </LOCATION> in the war has been scant.'' <PERSON> Mordechai </PERSON> <PERSON> Altshuler </PERSON>, an expert on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said the documents may establish a firmer figure on deaths than the current range of 1.25 million to 1.8 million. <PERSON> Altshuler </PERSON> said this could affect the overall estimte of 6 million dead. `` More material on the subject could change the picture one way or the other,'' he said. <PERSON> Krakowsky </PERSON> said it was premature to make a new estimate, but added he believed the death toll could be larger than believed. `` We saw names of death sites we had n't seen before and lists of names,'' he said. Another question raised is what kind of extermination methods the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> used in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and what role local collaborators were given, <PERSON> Krakowsky </PERSON> said. Until now it was believed that Russian Jewry perished mostly at the hands of German firing squads known as <ORGANIZATION> Einsatzgruppen </ORGANIZATION> who mowed them down at the edge of huge dirt pits in the initial stages of the war. `` It seems the process -LRB- in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> -RRB- may have been lengthier, with a wider use of gathering Jews first in ghettos and hiring local police to do some of the killing,'' <PERSON> Krakowsky </PERSON> said. He noted that some Soviet documents indicate there were more sites for rounding up Jews in towns and cities than previously thought. <PERSON> Karkowsky </PERSON> cited the town of <LOCATION> Homel </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION> where historians believed the Germans had organized one Jewish ghetto. New documents showed there were four ghettoes, suggesting more Jews may have been killed there than believed, he said. East German documents also may shed light on <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> theoretician <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, who was in charge of destroying synagogues, and on the shadowy alliance between <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s late Moslem Mufti, <PERSON> Haj </PERSON> <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON>, <PERSON> Krakowsky </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> also has begun contributing to knowledge of the Holocaust by agreeing to send an exhibition of wartime Judaic relics from <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. The items scheduled for display next April are `` part of an enormous collection that the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> had amassed for a memorial to an extinguished people,'' according to museum director <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> <PERSON> Meir </PERSON>.
