<HEAD>Communists Fight Uphill Battle Against Reform in Industrial Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSTRAVA, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This steel and coal town in <LOCATION> Moravia </LOCATION> has always been a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> stronghold, but even new party leader <PERSON> Karel </PERSON> <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON>'s roots in the region are n't enough to stem the quest for reform. The winds of change are strong even in this major industrial center, although `` we are always days behind <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Dusan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kubat </PERSON>, a journalist and staunch supporter of the Civic Forum reform movement. Civic Forum was a major force in the pro-democracy demonstrations that led to the downfall of former party chief <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON>. He was replaced by <PERSON> Urbanek </PERSON>, who is from <LOCATION> Bojkovice </LOCATION>, a village in southern <LOCATION> Moravia </LOCATION>. `` The situation is more complicated here,'' said <PERSON> Kubat </PERSON>, 30. `` People are more conservative. But I think most workers are already with us.'' Workers crowding a beer hall appeared to support his assessment. `` I am happy that the young ones started the fight,'' said steelworker <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Koukl </PERSON>. `` I am already 40 but I would like to join them. Everybody who has a sense of justice should join them.'' <PERSON> Stanislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Novak </PERSON>, a 40-year-old father of two, put down his glass of plum brandy and nodded: `` I would like my children to live in a better world.'' The Civic Forum's call for a two-hour general strike Monday was heeded by most plants here, with at least 20,000 workers taking to the streets after sirens signaled the start. At the Zarubek coal mine, however, the management `` did not let us gather and waited until the last moment before it allowed a group of miners to come up to take part in the strike,'' said a technician met at the gate, who refused to give his name. A rumor spread among miners before the strike that participants would lose their Christmas bonus of up to $ 900. Miners draw up to three times the national worker's pay. Once they work above ground, however, their wage is slashed substantially unless they are diagnosed to be suffering from silicosis. Complaints from their ranks that silicosis victims are increasingly being refused full pay were cited as a factor prompting the large miner participation in the strike. The local <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> organized a rally Wednesday on <LOCATION> Ostrava </LOCATION>'s People's Militia Square, at which traditional overall-clad workers were noticeably absent. One speaker was worker <PERSON> Jaroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Cahlik </PERSON>, who called on the <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> government `` to immediately stop the talks'' with the opposition. The mostly middle-aged crowd of about 5,000, including a group of army officers, broke into chants of `` Long live the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. We are still here,'' while a group of about 100 younger onlookers rose their arms in the `` victory'' sign of the opposition. `` They may still be here, but without power,'' said one bystander. <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Hnikova </PERSON>, a 29-year-old textile worker, joined in the pro-party chants. `` I will be with the party no matter what happens,'' she said. `` Of course there have been mistakes, but that will change now,'' she added after a brown-coated man whispered something into her ear. <LOCATION> Ostrava </LOCATION> has a mining engineering college where students are on an indefinite strike to press for the resignation of their rector, an orthodox Communist. The strike is being led by a teacher of Marxism-Leninism. Most of the mines in the region are no longer profitable but the party has opposed shutting them down for fear of stirring discontent. Their future is likely to figure in upcoming discussions about economic reforms. `` I am afraid that the economic situation will become worse,'' said mechanic <PERSON> Ladislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Mlynar </PERSON> outside <LOCATION> Ostrava </LOCATION>'s Hotel Atom as smoke billowed from a nearby blast furnace. `` The changes are so fast,'' said passerby <PERSON> Ondreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Imrich </PERSON>. `` I still fear that everything will end in a dead-end street again or that it will be suppressed.''
