<FIRST>r w AM-DebtsForgiven     11-30 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Debts Forgiven,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Reap $1.4 Billion Windfall as U.S. Forgives Penalties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> are the biggest winners, but all states will reap dividends from a decision by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> forgiving $ 1.4 billion in hotly-contested federal penalties under a huge family aid program. The penalties were owed by all 50 states because of alleged overpayments to beneficiaries under Aid to Families With Dependent Children, the federal-state welfare program for children who lack parental financial support. About 3.7 million families receive AFDC, the nation's largest cash assistance program. The biggest penalty to be wiped out belonged to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ $ 308.7 million, according to <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION>, a research group. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> owed $ 285.9 million, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> $ 134.0 million and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> $ 104.6 million. No state had avoided the penalties, although <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> owed a just $ 13,000 and <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> owed $ 18,000. Forgiving the debts and reforming the way states are penalized for overpayments `` is extremely significant,'' said <PERSON> Alicia </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelrine </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is something we've been pushing for for years It's a tough, technical, gut-it-out issue,'' she said. `` We were delightfully surprised,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, deputy secretary for income maintenance at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>, which owed $ 92.3 million. `` Obviously if we were forced to pay up, it would have made our system hemorrhage. It would have been disastrous,'' <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said. He said the state had been preparing to challenge the debt in court. The $ 1.4 billion is an estimate that includes only state overpayments made from the 1981 through the 1987 fiscal years. When figures for the 1988 and 1989 fiscal years are totaled, the amount of forgiveness could run as high as $ 2.2 billion, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>. The AFDC amnesty provision was contained in a $ 14.7 billion budget bill passed by both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last week in the rush to adjourn before Thanksgiving. <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> had backed a cheaper AFDC plan that did not include a full waiver of states' obligations, according to <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Delores </PERSON> <PERSON> Spitznagel </PERSON>. Still, she said, the budget measure is expected to be signed by the president. The revenue losses caused by the amnesty plan are more than offset in the measure by dozens of deficit-reduction provisions, including the extension into February of spending cuts imposed in October under the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law. The issue of AFDC overpayments has long caused rancor between states and the federal government. Since federal money is involved, the government monitors the program and assesses penalties when states accidentally make overpayments to beneficiaries or grant aid to people who do not qualify. Under program regulations in effect since 1983, any state with an error rate of 3 percent or above is subject to penalties and interest. But states have long held that the 3 percent `` tolerance level'' is arbitrary and ignores the realities of administering the program. States cite compliance figures showing that 41 states could not manage error rates of less than 3 percent in any year during the period. The new program enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> eliminates the 3 percent error rate, replacing it with a 4 percent figure or the national average, whichever is higher. Penalties would be assessed on a sliding scale reflecting the degree to which a state's errors exceed the national rate. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Support </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the division of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> that oversees <ORGANIZATION> AFDC </ORGANIZATION>, _ said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> apparently decided to give the program a fresh start. `` This gives all levels of government the opportunity to start with a clean slate and have a quality-control system that is operational and functional,'' <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> said. The new system begins in October 1991.
