<HEAD>Eds: Updates with security details, inserting 2 grafs after 17th
graf pvs, Two small</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Long experienced in dealing with invaders, the Maltese are blocking off roads and mobilizing the military _ and even the boy scouts _ to get ready for this weekend's superpower summit. They're also churning out T-shirts. Prime Minister <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenech </PERSON> <PERSON> Adami </PERSON> declared his island nation set for the arrivals Friday of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> for their talks aboard warships anchored in a Maltese harbor. `` The arrangements have gone beautifully,'' <PERSON> Fenech </PERSON> <PERSON> Adami </PERSON> told a news conference Thursday. <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>'s entire 1,200-man military and most of its 1,000 police officers have been assigned to security tasks for the meeting, manning roadblocks and checkpoints and making round-the-clock patrols on land and at sea. Even a shortage of tiny, wavable <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> flags has n't been enough to hamper the preparations, said <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafrace </PERSON>, who reports selling 160 American and Maltese flags a day from his little toy store behind the Palace of the Grand Masters in <LOCATION> Valletta </LOCATION>. `` They never sent the Russian ones,'' <PERSON> Stafrace </PERSON> said of his Italian suppliers. `` When Soviet sailors come ashore, they normally do n't have money and want to exchange. I traded for some pennants with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s face on them. But I've sold all them already.'' The Maltese government has come up with enough large <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags to decorate the public buildings in <LOCATION> Valletta </LOCATION>, a capital of steep narrow streets lined with ocher stone buildings. The stark, almost treeless setting could be mistaken for <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, if it were n't for the Christmas decorations strung across the main shopping streets in this heavily Roman Catholic country. And the signs in the distinctive Maltese language, influenced by Arabic, Italian, French and English. St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Street </PERSON>, for instance, becomes Triq <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gwann </LOCATION>. At a shop around the corner from <LOCATION> Triq </LOCATION> <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gwann </LOCATION> and just up from the deep harbor, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Civelli </PERSON> also had no Soviet flags, but was making up for it with colorful T-shirts showing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> floating along in separate fishing boats, shaking hands over the water in front of a Maltese cross. `` The whole world is looking at <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, I think. It's great,'' said <PERSON> Civelli </PERSON>. `` Tell your president to bring peace to the whole world. We've suffered a lot from wars.'' <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>'s wars began thousands of years ago, with Greeks, <ORGANIZATION> Etruscans </ORGANIZATION>, Carthaginians, Romans, <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> and Normans among the conquerors. In the 16th century, the knights of the Order of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> _ later known as the Knights of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> _ built the impressive fortresses that still dominate <PERSON> Valletta </PERSON>'s rocky skyline, and fought off the Ottoman Turks. <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> eventually kicked out the Knights of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, then Lord <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> kicked out the French. <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> was still under British rule through World War II, during which it survived ferocious bombing to remain a key Allied outpost in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>, just 58 miles south of <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>. Among the buildings badly damaged by German and Italian bombing was the 16th century hospital of the Knights of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, now rebuilt into a conference center. Its 530-foot-long Main <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> has been lined with tables and telephones for the 2,000 journalists accredited to cover the Gorbachev-Bush encounter from shore. Joining them are promoters of Maltese business opportunities eager to take advantage of the sudden attention _ and a few dozen khaki-clad scouts given the week off from school to run errands at the center. The Soviet missile cruiser Slava and the USS Belknap, a guided missile cruiser, are anchored in <LOCATION> Marsaxlokk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, a harbor at the southern tip of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, about a 30-minute drive from <LOCATION> Valletta </LOCATION>. Two small Maltese patrol boats sailed around the two warships Thursday, making sure no pleasure boats wandered nearby. Troops were stationed at <LOCATION> Marsaxlokk </LOCATION> to ensure security on land, and extra helicopter patrols of the area began Thursday, said Brig. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Spiteri </PERSON>, commander of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>'s armed forces. <PERSON> Spiteri </PERSON>, in charge of security for the summit, said Maltese officers began a thorough search of the airport Thursday in cooperation with American and Soviet experts. Patrols also watch the airport perimeter around the clock, he said. Some roads are already blocked to traffic, and more will be shut through the weekend, forcing the Anglican Cathedral in <LOCATION> Valletta </LOCATION> to cancel church services this Sunday. Still, hundreds of curious tourists and local people have already made the trek to look out from a once-sleepy fishing village at the ships bristling with armaments in the harbor. With many more rubberneckers expected Saturday and Sunday, the Maltese government has lined up several local bands and scheduled fireworks at <LOCATION> Marsaxlokk </LOCATION> to keep people occupied while they wait for history to be made offshore.
