<HEAD>State Eases Restrictions on Polish, Hungarian Reporters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it would allow journalists from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to apply for passes enabling them to move around the building unescorted. `` This step is being decided in light of the momentous steps toward freedom which have already taken place in both <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON>, the department's spokeswoman. Polish and Hungarian journalists who attend the daily press briefing or visit the press office on a regular basis can apply for building passes that give them the same privileges as colleagues from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other Western countries, <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. In May 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attempted to strengthen security at the building by barring unescorted visits by journalists from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Those reporters were required to have escorts when they attended the press briefing or conducted interviews with diplomats. The restrictions apply to all but Polish and Hungarian reporters.
