<HEAD>Mail Carriers Pay Customers for Errant Deliveries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th-10th grafs, bgng `During the...,' to restore dropped
first reference to Summers, delete it in following graf. Picks up 11th
graf pvs, `Of the...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERI WATERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Suburban postal carriers had such good results paying their customers for wrongly delivered mail that the program, intended as only a 60-day trial, will continue indefinitely, officials say. Since late September, every properly addressed letter delivered to the wrong address in suburban <LOCATION> Worthington </LOCATION> has cost carriers 25 cents out of their own pockets, but most carriers say they do n't mind They say their reputations are at stake. `` It's just a small way of telling our patrons that we are concerned about our jobs, and we try to do a decent job,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, a letter carrier for six years. `` We want them to know the whole postal system is not lousy.'' The 60-day trial program, modeled on one in Highpoint, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, was supposed to end last Saturday. Union and postal officials say the program has been successful considering the 125,000 pieces of mail the branch handles a day. `` People are taking a lot of pride in what they do, and it's worked well for them,'' said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gulley </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carriers </ORGANIZATION> local that represents <LOCATION> Worthington </LOCATION> branch employees <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said he had only one errant delivery during the two months of the program. `` I must have misread it,'' he said. During the first 60 days of the program, participating postal workers paid customers a total of $ 11 for 44 pieces of wrongly delivered mail, station manager <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Summers </PERSON> said. Most of the mistakes occurred in the past three weeks as substitutes filled in for vacations and illness of regular carriers, he said. The number of customer complaints has dropped from an average of 10 calls per week to one call a week since the program began, <PERSON> Summers </PERSON> said. Of the branch's 45 mail carriers, 25 participated in the program. Carriers at the station Wednesday who did not participate declined to be interviewed. <PERSON> Gulley </PERSON> said many carriers have high-volume business routes with mail bundled by other employees and do n't want to be responsible for someone else's mistakes. Carrier <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> offered another reason for program holdouts. `` It's the holidays, and I think a lot of people are afraid to join. A lot of them are on new routes, and they do n't want to be broke for Christmas. Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a letter carrier for three years, said her customers praised the program, and most assured her they would never turn her in. But Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said she paid 25 cents to a business customer during the program. `` I do n't know if I was the one that delivered that day, but I was the one they put down,'' she said. The program began after a local magazine chided the branch for its poor service, <PERSON> Summers </PERSON> said. He said carriers read about a similar program in Highpoint, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, and decided to try and salvage their reputations. The Highpoint program started last Dec. 23 with about 28 city and rural carriers of 79 total routes participating. So far, they've paid customers 78 quarters, said postmaster <PERSON> Enola </PERSON> <PERSON> Mixon </PERSON>. About 15 carriers have not paid out any quarters. `` We got, I do n't know how many nice compliments, the customers thought it was just great,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mixon </PERSON> said. From Dec. 23 to Jan. 24, they delivered more than a million pieces of mail and gave out 37 quarters, mostly on routes handled by substitutes. If substitutes did n't participate in the program, the quarter was paid by management and the union president at the time. Officials will meet in the next couple of weeks to assess the Highpoint program and see if any changes need to be made. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service officials and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carriers </ORGANIZATION>, which represents mail carriers, said they were not aware of similar programs elsewhere in the nation.
