<HEAD>Whooping Cranes Make Remarkable Comeback Following Losses in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKPORT, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The endangered whooping crane population, which suffered devastating losses in 1988, made a remarkable comeback this year, a wildlife refuge manager says. A total of 144 birds have been sighted at the <ORGANIZATION> Aransas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Rockport </LOCATION>, where they spend the winter before returning to their nesting grounds in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Buffalo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Giezentanner </PERSON>, refuge manager. `` We're really happy. As a matter of fact, we're ecstatic so far,'' he said Wednesday. Only 138 whooping cranes out of an expected 150 made it to the refuge last year. Biologists estimated that as many as a dozen birds may have died after leaving their Canadian habitat. One bird was shot by a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> lawyer, who paid a $ 15,000 fine, <PERSON> Giezentanner </PERSON> said. A good sign this year is that of the 21 whooping crane chicks sighted and tagged in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, all but one made it to the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> refuge. The increase in the world's only remaining naturally reproducing flock of whooping cranes is the result of favorable nesting conditions in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the fact that many of the birds are reaching breeding age, <PERSON> Giezentanner </PERSON> said.
