<SECOND>AM-Sedition Trial,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Law Experts Mixed on Usefulness of Sedition Tactic After Mistrial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal jury's rejection of seditious conspiracy charges against three radicals may signal that the little-used prosecution tactic will remain that way, a constitutional scholar said. Others cautioned that the loss may be a setback, but wo n't stop future sedition prosecutions. The nearly yearlong trial of <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON>, his wife, <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> ended in a mistrial Wednesday after the jury deadlocked on whether the three's alleged bombing exploits constituted racketeering. Prosecutors said they may decide Friday whether to retry the unresolved charges. On Monday, the jury issued a partial verdict clearing the three on the sedition charges that they plotted to overthrow the government. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinoy </PERSON>, a constitutional law expert at <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, interpreted that as a serious blow to the prosecution tactic of filing seditious conspiracy charges. `` I think there were defense lawyers definitely watching who will use -LRB- the <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> case -RRB- as a very strong indication that the seditious conspiracy technique has got to be totally abandoned,'' <PERSON> Kinoy </PERSON> said. `` I think the jury was reacting in a very fundamental and positive way to the basic constitutional protections of the people of this country in the exercise of their First Amendment rights.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON>, a defense lawyer who has been active in supporting radical causes, called the jury's decision `` a big setback'' for prosecutors, adding that it was `` a deserved one because what they've been doing for a long time is prosecuting revolutionary people in a far different way than anybody else, than murderers, thieves and so on.'' Prosecutors had claimed that the defendants belonged to a band of terrorists who conspired to commit bombings and bank robberies along the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> from 1976 to 1984 in a plot to overthrow the government. The seditious conspiracy charges trace their roots to the prosecution of Confederate spies in the Civil War era. The Sedition Act of 1918 was used against war protesters in World War I and to prosecute Puerto Rican nationalists in 1950. In April 1988, nine white supremacists were acquitted of seditious conspiracy in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. Prosecutors would n't comment on how they interpreted the <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> verdict. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Fink </PERSON>, a member of the defense team, said, `` I think they're going to give it up for a while. I think we dealt them a stunning and complete defeat.'' Still, <PERSON> Fink </PERSON> and retired <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> Professor <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Zinn </PERSON>, an expert on revolutionary history, said they do n't expect the government to abandon seditious conspiracy. `` I'm not saying they'll use it tomorrow. But they're there as handy weapons for them to use whenever they want to repress,'' <PERSON> Zinn </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Budd </PERSON> was deciding Thursday whether to try again on the unresolved racketeering charges. A statement may be made Friday, spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Spurlock </PERSON> said. A hearing is scheduled Jan. 5 in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to formally decide the disposition of the case. Jurors had also cleared Mrs. <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON> of a charge of racketeering. They deadlocked on two counts of racketeering against the two men and counts of racketeering conspiracy against all three. Each count carries a maximum penalty of 20 years and $ 20,000 in fines. While admitting nothing, the defense had said that prosecution was pointless since <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON> and <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> were already serving lengthy sentences for convictions on some of the bombings. Mrs. <PERSON> Levasseur </PERSON> was free on bail after serving 3 -LCB- years of a 5-year sentence for harboring a fugitive, her husband. The indictments were issued in May 1986 and the three defendants were all that remained of an original group of eight. Jury selection began in March 1988 and the actual trial began in January. Estimates of the cost ranged from $ 2 million to $ 10 million.
