provisions from the constitution that guarantee the Communists a monopoly on power. Whatever the change in its constitutional status, the party has 1.7 million members and controls the official media, police, armed forces and appointments in every operation from factories to village schools. `` The structure of power remains intact,'' <PERSON> Komarek </PERSON> said. `` It is only the facade which has collapsed, and the structure of power has receded into the background.'' `` Too many compromises are made, too much is spoken, too little is done. Relapses are still possible.'' The order to remove the fences reflected the new foreign policy <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON> said he seeks to implement. He has said he will choose a new government by Sunday that includes non-Communists. Members of Civic Forum could be among them. <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON> said Thursday he would accept opposition suggestions on who should serve in the new government. Civic Forum spokesman <PERSON> Jiri </PERSON> <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> said Wednesday night the opposition wanted a civilian Communist to run the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and a non-Communist to oversee police forces at the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. In a television address Wednesday night, <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON> appeared to promote himself as a figure of consensus to <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s 15.5 million citizens. He called for a reassessment of the 1968 <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact invasion, and pledged to negotiate withdrawal of the 80,000 Soviet soldiers stationed in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> ever since. The Soviet forces were seen as legitimizing party chief <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> and other Czechoslovak leaders installed by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> after the August invasion, but those men now have been ousted. <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON> said a Soviet withdrawal could occur only in `` an all-European framework.'' <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> said members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> had suggested repeal of the `` public order'' laws used to impose stiff fines or jail terms on anti-government protesters. The agency said the deputies, whom it did not identify, planned to submit that proposal and other legal measures to shorten pre-trial custody to a maximum of two months and remove the offense of `` abusing a religious function,' which has been used against priests. Priests must be licensed in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, and many have had to go underground after being barred from office by authorities. Deputies also want the independence of courts spelled out in a new consitution and seek laws to punish those who damage the environment, <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> reported. Nearly one-third of the nation's forests have been destroyed by acid rain and other pollution, and both air and water are badly polluted in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and several other cities.
