<HEAD>Hepatitis B Four Times as Common Among Blacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first nationwide scientific survey for hepatitis B infection shows the infectious liver disease is four times as common among blacks as whites, the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. In a survey of more than 14,000 people over five years, 4.8 percent showed signs in blood tests of having been infected with hepatitis B virus some time during their lives. Among blacks, 13.7 percent tested positive, compared with 3.2 percent among whites. Previous studies, including checks of blood samples given by blood donors, have pointed to an increased hepatitis B rate among blacks. But this study is the first among a statistically representative sample of people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said Dr. <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Alter </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> hepatitis specialist. The survey was conducted in the years 1976-1980 by the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>, but the results were reported Thursday for the first time The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> gave no explanation for the delay. Blacks' increased likelihood of getting hepatitis B sometime during their lives was especially evident in test results for people 65-74. In that age group, 39.6 percent of blacks had had hepatitis B infections, compared with 6.9 percent of whites. Hepatitis B is transmitted in ways somewhat similar to AIDS _ through sexual intercourse or direct contact with blood. Infections can cause inflammation of the liver, jaundice and flu-like symptoms. The disease can be prevented by a vaccine developed in 1982. Researchers believe as many as half the people infected with hepatitis B never suffer severe symptoms and never know they are infected. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> did not speculate on reasons for the increased prevalence of hepatitis B among blacks, but the Atlanta-based agency did say that the traditional targets for hepatitis B vaccinations _ health workers who handle blood, dialysis patients and some institutionalized people _ may be the wrong targets. Given the high prevalence of hepatitis B infections among blacks and a trend toward infection during adolescence, `` immunization of the traditionally targeted risk groups will not markedly affect the spread of infection in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Immunization programs need to include adolescents and young adults,'' the agency said. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> noted that survey findings showing higher rates of active infection for people in the 12-24 age group, compared with children under 11. Twenty thousand hepatitis B cases have been reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this year; many cases go unreported.
