<HEAD>Harvard Pollution Study is Target of NIH Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> is investigating procedures used in a study that helps set national air pollution standards amid allegations thata <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> professor ignored errors in the research, the university said Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> inquiry concerns the `` Six Cities'' study, which has been conducted at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> since 1974 to monitor the effects of air pollution, said <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Costa </PERSON>. <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Garsd </PERSON>, a former statistician at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> that he was dismissed from a research post in 1986 after he disclosed errors in the study to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Spengler </PERSON>, one of the professors working on the project. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> uses the information to set national air emission standards. `` They are checking some of the procedures and the data collection,'' Costa said. The action is the latest in a series of incidents that have raised questions about research integrity at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and other academic institutions. Last year, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> professor was forced to resign because of charges of plagiarism. <PERSON> Spengler </PERSON> was out of town Thursday and could not be reached for comment. But Costa, reading from a statement, said: `` We have absolutely no reason to believe that there is any evidence of scientific misconduct. We have every reason to believe that malevolence has led to the repetition of frivolous allegations.'' Costa said the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> inquiry apparently grew from the original allegations by <PERSON> Garsd </PERSON>, which he attributed to `` ill feeling'' from the ex-employee. <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadley </PERSON>, acting director of the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Integrity </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said she could neither confirm nor deny the existence of an inquiry. Speaking in general terms, however, she said an inquiry is a fact-finding process, in which officials determine if a formal investigation should be conducted into allegations of scientific misconduct. <PERSON> Garsd </PERSON>, who has sued <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> in a state court for alleged wrongful dismissal, now works for the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. He declined to comment on the case Thursday. But <PERSON> Garsd </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crimson </ORGANIZATION> in November 1988 that he sent several memos to <PERSON> Spengler </PERSON>, one of the professors working on the project, but received no response. And in a previous interview with The Wall Street Journal, <PERSON> Garsd </PERSON> said he found errors, including mistakes already published in journals and other scientific literature, that misstated the levels of certain air pollutants in the cities being studied by up to 20 percent. <PERSON> Garsd </PERSON> told the newspaper he had not contacted the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> and had been unaware of the inquiry. <PERSON> Spengler </PERSON> has said that any errors discovered by <PERSON> Garsd </PERSON> were corrected and did n't appear in print, the Journal reported.
