<HEAD>Satellite Now Expected to Fall to Earth Friday Night</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Rephrases last graf to say satellite slowed by atmosphere, pulled
in by gravity.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Solar Maximum satellite lost about 20 miles altitude in a 24-hour period Thursday, prompting the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> to predict that it will fall to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> about 10:45 p.m. EST on Friday. Most of the satellite will burn up in the atmosphere but up to a dozen larger pieces, weighing up to 100 pounds, may survive. Officials were n't ready to say in what part of the satellite's track they might come to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> `` We ca n't predict because there is about a six-hour margin of error in our calculations,'' said Capt. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Niemann </PERSON>, spokesman for the space command. `` That's four orbits of Earth.'' More than 80 percent of the satellite's path is over water and the chances of debris hitting anyone are considered remote. The only parts of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> under Solar <PERSON> Max </PERSON>'s ground track are <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and the extreme southern parts of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. Solar <PERSON> Max </PERSON>, which has been studying the sun for nearly 10 years, exhausted its positioning fuel recently and has been tumbling. Its electricity-producing solar panels and antenna were jettisoned by radioed command late last week. On Thursday, Solar <PERSON> Max </PERSON> was orbiting the globe every 88.4 minutes. When that period is down to 87.5 minutes, the satellite will be near enough to be slowed by the thickening atmosphere and pulled in by gravity.
