<FIRST>r a AM-Cocaine-HeartAttacks     11-30 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine-Heart Attacks,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Addicts Risk Heart Attacks Even After Withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cocaine addicts are in danger of suffering heart attacks even for a few weeks after they stop taking the drug, a group of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> researchers reported. Researchers from the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> report that the effects of cocaine may linger after withdrawal, altering the balance of chemicals in the brain that direct the cardiovascular system. Other scientists studying how cocaine affects the heart said the report offers `` compelling'' evidence of the risk of heart attacks and may have implications for drug treatment. The report appears in the Philadelphia-based journal <ORGANIZATION> Annals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in the issue being published Friday. Young abusers often experience fatal heart attacks while using cocaine. The 1986 deaths of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> basketball star <PERSON> Len </PERSON> <PERSON> Bias </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Browns </ORGANIZATION> football player <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> were both ascribed to cocaine-induced heart failure. But the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> study, which measured the heart function of 21 men who were in a substance abuse treatment program, discovered that addicts may experience abnormal heart activity for as long as four weeks after quitting cocaine. The report's lead author, Dr. <PERSON> Koonlawee </PERSON> <PERSON> Nademanee </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> medical center, warned that the first few weeks after withdrawal are crucial. `` I feel that during withdrawal, patients should be carefully monitored. The most important thing is to make sure the patient is completely abstinent from the drug,'' he said. The researchers found that eight of the 21 subjects had episodes of abnormal blood flow to the heart. They speculated that cocaine had upset the balance of chemicals in the brain that prevent the arteries from undergoing spasms, making heart attacks more likely. A heart attack causes the death of part of the heart muscle. It occurs when arteries that are narrowed or blocked keep a section of the heart from getting enough oxygen, which is carried in the blood. Cocaine restricts blood supply to the heart while increasing the heart rate, blood pressure and demand for oxygen. `` This is the strongest evidence to date that cocaine may cause spasming of the coronary arteries,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Isner </PERSON>, a cardiovascular medicine professor at <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` This really is incontrovertible evidence,'' he said, calling the study a `` spectacular report.'' But <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkerson </PERSON>, who studies the cardiovascular effects of cocaine at the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION>, cautioned that researchers do not have enough evidence to attribute the heart attacks to spasms of the arteries. Some scientists argue that the heart attacks could be caused instead by clots forming in the arteries or simply by blood flow inadequate to the heart's demand, he said. One member of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> group, Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorelick </PERSON>, now with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION>, said the group ruled out heart disease as the cause of the temporary heart abnormalities in the subjects. `` With longer periods of abstinence from cocaine, the -LRB- blood flow -RRB- went back to normal,'' he said. The report has immediate impact on how emergency room physicians will treat addicts experiencing chest pains, according to Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Spivey </PERSON>, chief of emergency room research at the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. `` It's going to make us realize that we're going to have problems -LRB- after withdrawal -RRB- with these cocaine addicts,'' said <PERSON> Spivey </PERSON>. The study `` opens our eyes'' to the value of preventive medical treatment for addicts withdrawing from cocaine, said Dr. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaer </PERSON>, a cardiologist at Rush-Presbyterian-St. <PERSON> Luke </PERSON>'s Medical Center in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> An estimated 25 million Americans have used cocaine at least once, including 6 million regular users and 1 million addicts, according to <PERSON> Isner </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gorelick </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> scientists now plan to focus on how cocaine use alters the chemicals in the brain to reduce the flow of blood to the heart and use other, more precise tests to examine heart function in cocaine addicts.
</TEXT>
