<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev-Excerpts     11-30 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Excerpts,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts from Mikhail Gorbachev's Speech at Rome's City Hall</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Following are excerpts from the official English-language text of Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s speech Thursday evening at the Campidoglio, <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s city hall: `` Our time is indeed a watershed of destiny ... We need spiritual values. ... We need a revolution of the mind. ... Of late, there has been much talk in the West that the world community will really become a single whole only if the ` other side,' i.e. the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, abandons its ideological and social values. Frankly, we are often told that we should purely and simply renounce socialism. Then, it is said, the world will become a nice and easy place to live in. It may sound simplistic, but I am deliberately reducing the argument to its essence. This is not the approach that the world needs as it is taking a great turn to a new era. It is another example of wishful thinking of the temptation to make policies on the basis of illusions rather than reality. ... We have abandoned the claim to have a monopoly on the truth; we no longer think that we are the best and that we are always right, that those who disagree with us are our enemies. We have now decided, firmly and irrevocably, to base our policy on the principles of freedom of choice, to build our economy and technology on the principle of mutual advantage, and to develop our culture and ideology through dialogue and acceptance of all that is applicable in our conditions, and hence, all that should be digested and used for our own progress. ... Unless we get rid of all things associated with the deformations of socialism in the past, we will not succeed in implementing the ideas of perestroika. ... We want to give second wind to the Soviet federation. Quite frankly, it will take deft handling. For inter-ethnic relations is a fragile and delicate sphere. But perestroika will enable us to solve this problem, crucial for the future of our state. We have changed our attitude to some matters _ such as, for example, religion _ which, admittedly, we used to treat in a simplistic manner. ... But now we not only proceed from the assumption that no one should interfere in matters of the individual's conscience; we also say that the moral values which religion generated and embodied for centuries can help in the work of renewal in our country, too. ... Today, the focus is on the socialist world. Having embarked upon the road of radical reform, the socialist countries, one after another, are crossing the line beyond which there is no return to the past. Nevertheless, it is wrong to insist, as many in the West do, that this is the collapse of socialism, the end of the socialist system. On the contrary, it means that the socialist process in the world, having accumulated extensive, although admittedly dramatic experience, will pursue its further development in a multiplicity of forms. It will thus acquire new opportunities for moving toward its just and noble goals, for releasing the enormous humanistic and democratic potential contained in the socialist idea. ... Let us leave it to experts in anti-communist propaganda to rejoice in the ` triumph of capitalism' in the Cold War. ... We hope that next year all European countries, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> will sign a historic document which will begin a new countdown in the area of military policy. ... My meeting with President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will, I am convinced, enable us to take a new constructive step in the movement ` from mutual understanding to mutual action' in Soviet-US relations. ... I believe that this year's events underscore the desirability of an all-European summit, a Helsinki-2 meeting. We could consider advancing its date from 1992 to, say, as early as 1990. ... In the final analysis we envision <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as a commonwealth of sovereign democratic states with a high level of equitable interdependence and easily accessible borders open to the exchange of products, technologies and ideas and wide-ranging contacts among people.''
</TEXT>
