<HEAD>As Airport Hotel Has Grand Opening, Radar Dispute Renewed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A hotel built too close to an airport radar because of a typographical error had its grand opening Thursday, renewing air traffic controllers' complaints that it blocks some radar coverage. The controllers dispute the government's claim that keeping planes at high altitudes above the blind spot is a temporary solution. `` It's just as bad if not worse,'' said <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Readio </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Controllers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` We still ca n't see airplanes in that area.'' Controllers said they would like to see the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> make a stronger response to an `` unsatisfactory condition report'' filed in May. At the time, controllers noticed that as the six-story Quality Suites hotel went up, more and more planes began disappearing from the radar screen. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> conducted tests that showed gaps in radar coverage up to about 2,000 feet in a corridor of air space up to seven miles wide and extending about 25 to 35 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jetport </LOCATION>. Until the radar can be moved, the agency adopted interim guidelines under which airplanes going through the area are kept well above 2,000 feet, said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Claxton </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> tower manager at the airport. `` I ca n't say the problem is completely solved,'' <PERSON> Claxton </PERSON> said. `` We set up the interim procedures until the problem is solved. If it was a real safety issue, the radar would have been moved two months ago, or we'd put a new one in.'' <PERSON> Claxton </PERSON> said only small planes are affected, because larger planes are not flying that low when they are 30 miles out. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Breen </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> representative of the air traffic controllers association, said controllers also have to keep jetliners out of the area even if they are at a high altitude because pilots can not be advised about what might be flying under them. Ms. <PERSON> Readio </PERSON> said commercial flights from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> often go near the area, and controllers have to make sure they stay away from the blind spot. `` We ca n't tell them what's there,'' <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> said from <LOCATION> Bradley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, just north of <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> `` The system could be safer by getting this radar moved soon.'' <PERSON> Claxton </PERSON> said the radar might be moved within the next year. `` We're going to move the radar,'' <PERSON> Claxton </PERSON> said. `` Where we're going to move it, I'm not sure It kind of sits low on the airport, and things were fine until the building came along.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said it never objected to the hotel construction because when the project was first proposed, the developer's plans contained a typo that indicated the building would be 12,000 feet from the runway when it was in fact just 1,200 feet from the runway. <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> blames the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> for the mixup. `` Twelve-hundred feet and 12,000 feet are quite a bit different,'' <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> said. `` Typo or not, you'd think somebody would have noticed it.''
