<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> agent who fled to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> just before he was charged with passing secrets was recently ordered expelled from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said Thursday. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government urged <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to permanently bar <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, a defector wanted on an espionage charge who has made extended visits to the eastern block country, said the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity. In 1985, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> eluded <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> surveillance near his home in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, and fled the country two days before he was charged in a warrant with passing secrets to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He later turned up in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> announced nearly a year after his defection that it had given <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> political asylum. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, 37, is charged with selling secrets to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for $ 6,000 in 1984 during a trip to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. He is said to have exposed the network of <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> contacts in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, a spy post for which he was trained but never assigned to because he was fired in 1983. `` He certainly gave away the entire <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> operation in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>, author of the 1988 book about the <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> case entitled `` The Spy Who Got Away.'' Wise reported in the book that <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> was paid more than $ 150,000. One official confirmed that <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> was still in the Soviet bloc. Wise said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> was probably in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> where he has an apartment and a nearby summer house. Besides exposing dead-drop locations and codes the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> employed to contact Soviet contacts, <PERSON> Wise </PERSON> said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> exposed details of electronic eavesdropping the agency conducted in the Soviet capital. `` There was n't much he did n't give up,'' Wise said. <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> made a veiled reference to <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>'s expulsion when asked by reporters Wednesday about cooperation between intelligence agencies of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and Eastern bloc nations <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> cited the case of a `` a prominent defector from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> -LRB- who -RRB- was permanently expelled from a bloc country which had provided him comfort and sanctuary in the past.'' `` And that would have been contrary to the wishes of the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, who did n't identify <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> or the country by name. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials confirmed a report in Thursday's editions of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Times that <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> was referring to <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>'s expulsion from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> Asked about the report, <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Lt. Col. <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Horvach </PERSON> said in a telephone interview, `` It's news to me.'' <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> refused to comment about the case. Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>'s handler during a recent visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON>, who was the No. 2 KBG official at the time he was directing <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> case was not discussed during the meeting at <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. The meeting was scheduled `` only to talk about areas where there could be discussion on cooperation in the law enforcement area,'' including efforts to combat terrorism, <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. Wise, who interviewed <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> for his book during a visit to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, said the former <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> agent spent a lot of time in that country, enjoying visits to <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bolatov </LOCATION>, a resort area. `` I would doubt if he would set foot in the West'' for fear of being snatched by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agents, <PERSON> Wise </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> was even nervous about visiting <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, where he feared the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> could inject a tranquilizer in his arm and spirit him across the Austrian border, <PERSON> Wise </PERSON> said. Given the current political climate in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Wise </PERSON> said it is most likely that <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> has returned to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where he would feel safe from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to arrest him. While <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> would not be subject to extradition from a Western country because espionage is a political crime, <PERSON> Wise </PERSON> pointed out that he might feel threatened by the new overseas snatch authority conferred on the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. A legal opinion issued last June by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said that the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> had the legal authority to seize <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fugitives overseas without the permission of a foreign government. Wise reported in his book that <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> was paid handsomely for his spying by the Soviets. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> had $ 150,000 in a Swiss bank account before he defected and afterwards, his wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>, led <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents to a spot in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> desert where her husband had buried $ 10,000 worth of gold and other valuables. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>'s wife, who lives in the <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> area with the couple's son, could not be reached for comment.
