<FIRST>u a AM-AMARights     11-30 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AMA Rights,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMA Issues Patient ``Bill of Rights''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH NORDGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Patients have a right to basic health care from attentive, courteous doctors who tell them their choices for treatment, according to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s first `` Patient Bill of Rights.'' In a brief list of six principles, the nation's largest physicians' organization spells out the responsibilities doctors have to those who seek their help. The document issued Thursday is being presented for approval at next week's meeting in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION>. The bill is a `` reaffirmation of what is inherent in the relationship of physician to patient,'' the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s general counsel, <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, said in a telephone interview Thursday. `` It is coming now not because physicians need to be reminded'' of their responsibilities, he said, but because patients need to `` know and retain their trust in the basic elements of their relationship with their physician.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said the bill of rights was devised over the past year by the association's Council on Ethical and Judicial Affairs. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION> may accept it as is, or send it back to the council for further explanation, he said. The bill of rights is `` something that patients can understand _ simple, straightforward and the minimum that patients can expect from their physicians,'' he said. It includes a patient's `` right to essential health care'' regardless of ability to pay and suggests in an attached commentary that `` physicians have a responsibility to provide some uncompensated care to the indigent.'' A critic of the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> immediately took issue with the document, saying that in many ways, the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> circumvents the bill's intent in its everyday actions. `` These are sort of apple pie, motherhood ideas, rights, which none could disagree with,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citzen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. `` There are two main problems: They -LRB- the principles -RRB- are n't enforceable and many of them run completely contrary to what the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> does and stands for,'' said <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, whose group, a Washington-based consumer health research and advocacy organization, is in its 18th year `` If they took action to ensure that these rights were translated into results for patients, it would be another thing. `` The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> has hardly been at the forefront ... in ensuring that, for example, patients have access to information showing differences between hospitals and doctors.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> discounted the criticism, saying the bill of rights is `` valuable and needed.'' Patients, the document says, have the right to receive information and know the `` benefits, risks and financial costs'' of their treatment. They also have the right to make their own decisions on the treatment of their illness, it says. `` The patient has the right to courtesy, respect, dignity, responsiveness and timely attention,'' according to one article of the bill, which adds: `` Physicians have an obligation to schedule their appointments ... in a way that respects the value of the patient's time.'' The document's final principle says a patient `` has the right to continuity of health care.'' According to the attached commentary, `` The physician may not discontinue treatment of a patient as long as further treatment is medically indicated, unless alternative arrangements are available.''
</TEXT>
