<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Thursday filled two vacancies on the board of the <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on the eve of a scheduled vote to replace the organization's president <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Wear </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> gave so-called recess appointments to former Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Erlenborn </PERSON>, R-Ill., and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blakely </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> to sit on the board that oversees the independent agency that gives legal help to the nation's poor <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made the appointments during the year-end recess of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, thus avoiding <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation proceedings. Under the Constitution, people given recess appointments can serve until the end of the congresional session _ in this case the end of 1990. The board meeting scheduled for Friday is the latest in skirmishing between two factions over the nature of legal services. The corporation's board has been a battleground for conservatives seeking to limit legal services, particularly class-action lawsuits against the government over welfare and other social programs. Conservatives also object to legal services representing plaintiffs in lawsuits to force hospitals to give abortions to indigent women. This faction held a 6-5 majority on the board until two vacancies recently occurred, said <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defenders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The group monitors the agency and supports efforts to allow legal services lawyers to provide a full range of representation, she said. Supporters of a broader range of legal services held a 5-4 majority on the board before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made the appointments on Thursday. The board was scheduled Friday to consider a move to oust Wear and demand an accounting of more than $ 100,000 spent to hire a former <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration official to provide outside legal advice, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. The money was paid for legal opinions provided by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, a former assistant attorney general in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and a conservative activist, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. Those opinions include one by <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> that the corporation is unconstitutional. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said her organization did not know how <PERSON> Erlenborn </PERSON> would vote if he attended Friday's meeting. Now a private attorney in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Erlenborn </PERSON> was considered a supporter of legal services when he represented a suburban <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> congressional district, she said. Earlier this year, conservative activists successfully lobbied the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to stop the appointment of former Republican Rep. <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> to the board. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> had angered conservatives by stating he would not support restrictions on the activities of legal aid attorneys.
