<HEAD>Former Neighbor Charged In 20-year-old Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty years after <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nason </PERSON> was killed, a former neighbor appeared in court Thursday and was charged with the slaying, and published reports said the man's own daughter gave the information leading to his arrest. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, 50, was arrested Tuesday at his home in <LOCATION> Carmichael </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, and charged with murdering the 8-year-old girl. He was held without bail on one count of murder. Investigators would not identify the witness who provided the tip that led to the arrest. But the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION>, quoting an unidentified law enforcement source, reported Thursday that <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>'s daughter, a former classmate of the dead girl, came forward and told investigators she witnessed the 1969 slaying. The source said the daughter had repressed all memory of the event, but finally recalled seeing her father bludgeon her friend to death with a rock in his van. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> disappeared while playing after school near her home in <LOCATION> Foster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on Sept. 22, 1969. Her disappearance led to an extensive search in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area. A $ 20,000 reward was offered for the arrest and conviction of her killer by the employer of <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Nason </PERSON>, the girl's father. The girl's remains were found four months later under an old mattress at an abandoned gravel pit near the <LOCATION> Crystal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reservoir </LOCATION> about 20 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. She had been killed with a blunt instrument that fractured her skull, investigators said. <PERSON> Nason </PERSON>, who lives in the same <LOCATION> Foster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> home with his wife, <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON>, said he never gave up hope a suspect would be arrested in his daughter's killing. `` The law has a very long memory,'' he said. `` After 20 years _ almost on the anniversary and it's pretty close to the day _ it's something you hope for all this time. <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mateo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dow </PERSON> said detectives believe <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> killed the girl because he had tried to sexually molest her. At <LOCATION> Carmichael </LOCATION>, a suburb of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, a close friend of <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> said the arrest shocked them both. `` I talked to him today, and he's still in shock. He has absolutely no idea what's happening or why or anything,'' said the friend, who declined to identify herself. `` I certainly do believe he is innocent.'' <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> retired to the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> area several years ago after a long career with the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mateo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said the friend. The woman said <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> is a licensed real estate agent but is not currently working. `` He's an outgoing man, a delightful person,'' the woman added.
