nterview with his party's daily that he is `` certain'' the legal guarantee of the party's leading role in political life will be eliminated from <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>'s constitution. `` Some kind of coalition'' will then govern <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Titma </PERSON> said in the interview, printed in the Sunday edition of the Sovietskaya <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> newspaper. The political changes in the Baltic republics come against the backdrop of upcoming local elections across the country, which begin in some parts of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on Dec. 10. For the first time nationwide, voters will be offered a choice of candidates for their local `` soviets,'' or governing councils. Party officials in the once independent Baltic republics have said they must have a free hand to set policies popular with voters or risk defeat. <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, who was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, traveled to <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> Wednesday to take part in a high-level party meeting. He spoke Thursday to Vilnius-based delegates to a special congress of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which will open Dec. 19. On the congress agenda is a draft program proclaiming the republic's party `` a political force in the creation of an independent, law-governed <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> state.'' Since the days of Soviet founder <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leaders have rejected autonomy for local party organizations in the name of `` democratic centralism.'' Lithuanian party leaders were summoned to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Nov. 16 to make their intentions known to the full Communist Party Politburo, including Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> strongly opposes plans for the <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> party to separate from the national <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which he has headed since March 1985. At the meeting in <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> advocated more rights for the local parties in the 15 constituent Soviet republics, but only `` within the renewing <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. In <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, the dissident Communists called for renouncing the `` utopian goal of building Communist society and the dogmatic interpretation of Marxism-Leninism,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Despite criticism of the dissidents, the Latvian Politburo admitted `` it was losing the initiative'' and decided to organize working groups to draft the rules and program of the <LOCATION> Latvian </LOCATION> party, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> also scheduled a plenum of its <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in January `` to renew its composition'' and make changes in the party apparatus, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said, indicating the likelihood of sweeping personnel changes. The declaration of the 39 Latvian Communists was printed by <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>'s major party and government newspapers, according to a telex sent to the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> bureau of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> by the Latvian Popular Front, a grassroots pro-reform group.
