<HEAD>House Delays Tax Debate As Democratic Leaders Scramble for Votes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> adjourned Thursday without tackling a $ 1.2 billion tax-hike package that signaled the end of the economic boom dubbed the `` <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> miracle'' and triggered a `` firestorm'' of taxpayer protest. A Statehouse switchboard operator said she was handling 100 calls every 15 minutes from irate taxpayers. Speaker <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Keverian </PERSON>, after a day of vote hunting, recessed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> without opening debate on the package approved Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. It includes hikes in sales, capital gains and gasoline taxes. `` Considerable time has gone by today and I apologize to many of you who have been here waiting for the beginning of debate,'' <PERSON> Keverian </PERSON> said. `` Our position is the same as it was. We intend to make some refinements and some suggestions tomorrow.'' The committee's package would add two cents to the sales tax, increase the gas tax by 10 cents over the next two years and hike capital gains from 5 percent to 7.5 percent. Most increases would take effect Jan. 1, 1990, but the capital gains would be retroactive to last January. The proposal is the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s latest move to deal with the deficit, which a Ways and Means staffer said had swelled to $ 825 million. As the committee sent the proposal to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> held hearings on a $ 350 million House-approved package of spending cuts. <PERSON> Keverian </PERSON> said later Thursday the Democratic leadership would propose an amendment to lower the sales tax increase to 6 cents on the dollar, up from the current 5 cents. That would cost $ 190 million in new revenue this fiscal year and about $ 400 million next year. <PERSON> Keverian </PERSON> said the loss would be made up with additional cuts and possibly with additional revenue in the tax package. He said he did not anticipate any other significant changes, although he would not predict the outcome of a vote on a rank-and-file amendment he said he expects will be offered to remove the capital-gains tax hike from the bill. Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who had suggested he had some reservations about the package, urged approval, saying he realized taxes were unpopular but elected officials should take a tough stand. `` If there's anything we've got to have now it's fiscal stability,'' the governor said. `` And that's what this package is going to bring.'' The Republican minority leader, Rep. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, said the size of the package and the leadership's effort to rush it through were a losing combination. `` They failed to get it out because they're pushing an outrageous bill,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said, adding that it had set off a `` firestorm of angry criticism from an angry public.'' `` The answer should be the same no matter what the package is. The answer should be no,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said. Rep. <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> <PERSON> Clapprood </PERSON>, a Democrat and supporter of the package, predicted the sales tax increase would be lowered. `` I think it is clear as the package stands, we are short of the 81 votes needed to pass it,'' she said. <PERSON> Clapprood </PERSON> suggested shutting off the Statehouse switchboard and locking lawmakers in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chamber to get the bill passed. She said she got one call at home at 4:30 a.m. Thursday from a woman opposed to higher taxes. `` The whole state of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> has called,'' said one of the <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION>'s two switchboard operators who declined to give her name. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxation </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> was trying to con voters into accepting taxes by slashing human services and education budgets. `` The point is, are we going to give into this kind of blackmail?'' she said.
