<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv01   11-30 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 01,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, Dec. 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Are Price-Earnings Ratios A Guide?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ratio of price to earnings long has been one of the most popular measurements of value in the stock market, so well known that it is published each business day in many newspapers. It is easily comprehended, being nothing more than the multiple of per-share earnings that buyers are willing to pay for a company's stock. Example: Earnings of $ 2 a share, price $ 24, equals P-E of 12. This very simplicity, however, provokes critics into warnings that it is too simplistic, too dated and too variable to provide fully reliable information. Simplistic? To measure value by P-E alone may mean ignoring management changes or developing problems. Dated? It measures past performance, not that of the future. Variable? P-Es bounce all over the lot. This latter criticism is becoming one of the paramount considerations these days, one that is perhaps as difficult to fathom as any in the marketplace. The reason: The level of P-Es varies enormously, depending on myriad factors. If these factors were strictly financial, perhaps they could be understood. But they include mass psychology, cultural change, relations between nations, threats of war, investment money available, world confidence and on and on. As a result, the market's average P-E can vary sharply from year to year, from one industry to another, from country to country. While you might be able to tell if one company's P-E is out of line with the market as a whole, how do you know that the market's average P-E also is n't out of whack At the end of October, according to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dessauer </PERSON>, an independent analyst who follows stocks throughout the world, P-Es in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> were 11.8, in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> 13.7 and in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> 50.1. Which is too high, which too low? What are the factors _ cultural, economic, psychological _ that justify such differences? And what do you make of <PERSON> Dessauer </PERSON>'s finding that at the end of 1982, when the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic expansion began, comparable ratios were 10.8 in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, 10.1 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 22.2 in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>? <PERSON> Dessauer </PERSON>, publisher of <PERSON> Dessauer </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, traced average P-Es in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for several decades and found variability that many would consider surprising. A general trend toward higher P-Es developed through the 1950s and 1960s. In 1950, investors paid on average only seven times earnings for the stocks in the Dow Jones industrial average. By 1959 the average had risen to 18.4 times earnings and it peaked in 1961 at 21.7 times. The trend went into reverse in the 1970s. Perhaps because of rising oil prices, double-digit inflation and growing budget deficits, investors lowered the prices they were willing to pay for stocks. By 1979 the Dow's P-E ratio was down all the way to 6.8. From that extreme low, the Dow's P-E began rising again in the 1980s _ until the great crash of October 1987. Recently it stood at 11.3, down from a 1987 average of 15.8. What does the future hold? To even attempt answering that you would have to consider the possibilities for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy, the consequences of the Cold War ending, the contributions that will be made by changes in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the growth rate of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economy, the amount of investment money available That might be a beginning; the end could never be sighted. The amount of research necessary, to say nothing of its quality, would consume so much time that it could n't keep pace with changes, including those in the average P-E. Opinions are always possible, however, and <PERSON> Dessauer </PERSON> believes `` the overwhelming need to invest huge amounts of surplus capital can be expected to overcome stock market jitters.'' He believes the trend will gather momentum and become self-reinforcing. His forecast: `` Look for world stock markets, pushed by the forces of a huge global savings pool, to be generally strong in 1990 and into 1991.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for PMs Friday, Dec. 1.</NOTE>
