<FIRST>a i BC-Asia-1990s Adv03-1stAdd-SUB b0737 11-30 0920</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Asia-1990s, Adv 03-1st Add-SUB, b0737,0943</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS 8th graf, Singapore's President ... coming years.,
to fix title of Lee Kuan Yew to prime minister sted president. The 1st
take, b0736, will not be retransmitted.</HEAD>
<HEAD>HONG KONG: military crackdown.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The future of <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s decade of market-oriented economic reforms, under which <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economy staged a remarkable recovery after the ruinous 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, is particularly murky. `` To get rich is glorious'' was the phrase that moved the masses in the 1980s, but it has fallen out of favor with the ascendancy this year of ideological hard-liners. If conservatives such as Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> win the power struggle, the open-door policy would slow and more emphasis would be placed on central planning, which would be bitterly opposed by coastal regions that prospered greatly during <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s reforms. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s uncertain future was summed up recently by <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador to <PERSON> Beijing </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lilley </PERSON>, who said: `` It may be some years before we can put a name or theme to the new chapter <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will write in the 1990s. In the meantime, we must be prepared for twists and turns that may defy attempts'' at labeling. A crisis also could occur in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, a fledgling democracy where President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has said she will not seek re-election when her term expires in 1992. No strong candidate has emerged as her heir apparent on the politically fractured archipelago. <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohamad </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Suharto </PERSON> are strong leaders who also may leave the scene in the coming years. `` Every leader but one will change'' in the region, said <PERSON> Broadfoot </PERSON>. He expects only the Sultan of <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION> to still be in power at the turn of the century. One territory that is almost assured of a rough decade is <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> will hand over to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1997. Fewer and fewer of the colony's 5.7 million people have faith in Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s promise that <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> can maintain its capitalist lifestyle for 50 years and enjoy a `` high degree of autonomy,'' particularly since the suppression of the pro-democracy movement in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Huge numbers of people uncertain about the future are emigrating from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. A foreign passport is the most prized possession in the colony, and residents are sparing no effort to secure one. Marriage counselors report booming business from people desperately seeking foreign national spouses. The government, in estimates often criticized as too conservative, believes 42,000 people will emigrate in 1989 and another 55,000 will leave the following year. Many highly educated white-collar workers are among those leaving, leading to a brain drain that could reduce the territory's economic competitiveness Adding to the territory's headache are the approximately 57,000 Vietnamese boat people who have sailed to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> seeking asylum. The squalid camps in which they are housed could erupt in violence if the government carries through plans to send most of them back to their homeland against their will. Two of the other `` little dragons'' _ <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> _ show promise for furthering what <PERSON> Mushkat </PERSON> calls `` the slow and painful process'' of democratic change in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, which has a long history of authoritarian rule. For example, the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is slowly giving up its monopoly on political power in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. `` Democratization shall not move backward in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> unless the economy collapses or in case of a war, neither of which looks very likely,'' said <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ya-li </PERSON>, a political commentator at <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taiwan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. But <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> may experience some social instability because of a problem also faced by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ a population that has not seen its standard of living increase as quickly as national wealth. Property prices have skyrocketed in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, and most middle-class families have lost all chance of buying their own homes. Crime has increased to the point where sales of luxury foreign cars have fallen sharply because businessmen say the vehicles make them targets of blackmail. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the average person lives in cramped housing, suffers a long commute through congested traffic and pays prices 20 percent to 30 percent higher than in other industrial nations. Says <PERSON> Broadfoot </PERSON>: `` You'll see a much greater emphasis on quality of life in <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'' during the 1990s. In <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, the 1990s will begin with a number of thorny security issues, including the Cambodian civil war in which the genocidal <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> is among several groups fighting for power. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> will be negotiating the future of six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases on the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> whose lease expires in 1991. Many influential politicians oppose the bases, and there has been some indication of growing sentiment in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>' armed forces against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> facilities. But perhaps the most interesting security question will be what <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> does to protect its growing economic interests in the region. <PERSON> Broadfoot </PERSON> sees <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> likely flexing greater military strength. `` I do n't think the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will be able to continue to be the defense umbrella of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> to the extent that it has been,'' he said. A stronger Japanese military will undoubtedly rekindle painful memories throughout the region of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s efforts to carve a subservient <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> Co-Prosperity Sphere during the World War II era. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> may choose to protect its investment through the use of foreign aid designed to promote stability in the region, but that could help create a zone of influence that also could lead to anti-Japanese sentiment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 3</NOTE>
