<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 9-10, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mitsubishi Montero: As Much Beauty as Beast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 It's tall, boxy, big and truck-like, but in its own way, the 1990 <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> Montero 4-Door RS is as much beauty as beast. True, there's no refined leather interior or woodgrain trim, but there is lumbering V-6 power and decent handling to impress. There are no comfort-making, front-seat middle armrests, the steering wheel is large and truckish, and the <PERSON> Montero </PERSON>'s radio is a bit of a reach at the bottom of the center dashboard console. But the Montero does offer lots of legroom and headroom, thanks to its unusually tall profile, and it climbs inclines with gusto. In sum, the <LOCATION> Montero </LOCATION> is a substantial, serious vehicle with a rugged character. It's not a dressed-up pretty face on the road. That did n't stop Motor Trend magazine from naming the 1989 Montero 4-Door the top buy among sport utility vehicles. The vehicle returns for 1990 virtually unchanged mechanically and in design. Among the key attributes of the Montero that Motor Trend noted was its interior space: at 94.9 cubic feet of cargo capacity with the rear seat folded, it's the largest of its class. The magazine was n't exaggerating. The room inside the test vehicle was something to behold. Three adults were comfortable in the bench back seat, and legroom there was admirable, thanks to the high perch of the back seat that meant legs were extended mostly downward, rather than horizontally. Way back in the cargo area, I could even sit straight up on the carpeted floor with my back against the rear seat and conveniently fit my legs inside. The 43.4 cubic feet left plenty of room for tailgating, and as mentioned, it could be enlarged to 94.9 cubic feet if the rear seat was folded. The rear gate swung open sideways, not pulling downward. Even on a slight slope, the gate opened easily and held _ not swinging back on me. Of course, I did have a big step up to get inside because of its high ground clearance for off-roading. There also was good passenger visibility, thanks to the high seating perch in the 74.4-inch-high Montero, which is taller than competitors <ORGANIZATION> Isuzu </ORGANIZATION> Trooper and Jeep Cherokee. Inside the Montero, handles seemed to be about everywhere, especially for rear-seat passengers. They could grab either of two handles by the rear doors to help them scramble up, or they could use the cut-out-style headrests on the front seats to help them get situated inside. The <PERSON> Montero </PERSON> also had a unique inclinometer in the middle of the dashboard. It was an encased blue and black ball that rolled in its case with the movement of the vehicle. When the ball went nearly black, I knew the vehicle was in a dangerously inclined position. But do n't try to watch the ball as you drive, or you may wind up off the road as I did. <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> notes that the inclinometer's indicator should be checked when the vehicle is at a standstill Still, just its moving presence on the dash served as a reminder that the Montero, like all sport utility vehicles, has a different center of gravity than cars do and must be driven with care. The test vehicle went from two-wheel - to four-wheel-drive and back again with the help of automatic free hubs They automatically locked or unlocked the front wheels according to the setting on the transfer shift lever inside, next to the regular transmission gear shifter. The two-door <PERSON> Montero </PERSON> has been sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since February 1984, but the four-door model did n't arrive until August 1988. Spokeswoman <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stearn </PERSON> said the four-door was needed as more Americans began using sport utilities as station wagons and for rural and off-road trips for families. Sales of Monteros grew from 2,348 in 1984 to 10,924 in 1987, then fell to 8,521 in 1988. But in the first 10 months of this year, sales were up again, from 5,903 in the January-October period in 1988 to 9,792. <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> says the four-door <LOCATION> Montero </LOCATION> buyer is typically male -LRB- 74 percent -RRB- and married -LRB- 88 percent -RRB-. But studies show it's not unusual for their wives to drive the Montero more than they do. Median age of the male buyer is 39, and 66 percent are college graduates, the company says. Average family income is $ 75,500, and 40 percent are in professional and technical jobs. An additional 15 percent are managers. The Montero is not at the bottom of the sport utility field, pricewise. Starting price for a four-door with V-6 engine and manual transmission is $ 15,519, compared with $ 14,249 for an Isuzu Trooper -LRB- trim levels may differ slightly, too -RRB-. The test vehicle, a middle range RS model with four-speed automatic transmission and options, topped out at more than $ 21,000. Consumer Reports magazine did not list an owner trouble record for the <LOCATION> Montero </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
