<FIRST>s w BC-Soviet-LongWinter Adv03   11-30 1221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Soviet-Long Winter, Adv 03,1255</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cold and Snowy Gray Skies Set Mood for Soviet Winter of Discontent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As snow begins to fall and the sky turns gray, Soviet citizens enter a long winter of discontent over barren store shelves, strikes and ethnic clashes that, far from being halted by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms, often have worsened. `` There's much that we'd like to have, but the Russian people are used to difficulties,'' said <PERSON> Luda </PERSON> <PERSON> Panina </PERSON>, 33, as she sold red carnations outside a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> subway station on a cold, snowy day. Russians _ and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s more than 100 other national groups _ have endured hardships for decades, but the difference is that now they expect more, both from <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and from his perestroika program that 4 -LCB- years ago promised to make their lives better. Preparing for his shipboard summit with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> this weekend, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> indicated a principal goal of the talks would be to discuss easing of international tensions so that he could focus more on problems at home. `` To put it in a nutshell, we need a normal external environment for our domestic work,'' he said. The country has been torn by long-simmering ethnic, economic and environmental woes that the leadership previously ignored or stifled, but which have surfaced as `` glasnost,'' or openness, exposes harsh realities. Inflation, crime and budget deficits, around for decades, were hushed up until glasnost brought out the shocking numbers: crime up 34 percent in the first 10 months of 1989 over the same period last year, a budget deficit reaching 120 billion rubles -LRB- $ 194 billion -RRB-, inflation pegged by one economist at 4 percent to 5 percent yearly. Ethnic tensions among the myriad Soviet peoples _ many of whom were brutally oppressed under dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> _ have pitted Armenians against <PERSON> Azerbaijanis </PERSON>, ethnic Turks against Uzbeks and Russian minorities against Estonians, Latvians, Lithuanians, Ukrainians and Moldavians. Ethnic clashes have taken more than 300 lives, by official count. In addition, growing campaigns for independence in many of the 15 constituent Soviet republics, especially in the <ORGANIZATION> Baltics </ORGANIZATION>, are threatening the very glue that holds the union together. Strikes by coal miners, angry about official inattention to their hazardous work conditions and poor lifestyles, have depleted fuel supplies going into the winter. In the southern republic of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, the government ordered businesses to switch days off to Wednesdays and Thursdays because of an electricity shortage, caused in part by the shutdown of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s nuclear power plant after last year's devastating earthquake. Outright economic sabotage is afoot as well. <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> blockaded the ethnic hotspot of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> for two months, preventing trainloads of fuel, food and raw materials from getting through. The blockade delayed reconstruction of the area leveled by the Dec. 7, 1988, earthquake that killed 25,000 Armenians. Officials now say rebuilding will take three years, one more than planned. Other headaches the nation and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> have suffered include the 1986 <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear power plant explosion and fire that, according to one Soviet newspaper, led to the deaths of 250 people and cost billions of rubles, a gas pipeline blast in June that killed more than 600 passengers on passing trains, and extensive water and air pollution. To many Soviets, however, their mood depends largely on what there is to eat and wear. For the most part, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms have brought not improvements in Soviets' standard of living, but more of what people here call `` deficits,'' shortages of products that have led to the widespread rationing of butter, cheese, meat, sugar and tea. Some economists even propose rationing everything, to prevent the hoarding that is now common. As Soviets approach the end of the year, many would agree with a prediction made months ago. `` One can expect that the year 1989 will be the most unsuccessful of all those we have lived through,'' <PERSON> Vasily </PERSON> <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON>, a specialist in economic affairs, wrote in April. Statistics tell the 287 million Soviets what they already know from painful experience: _ Of 211 food products, a consumer demand institute found only 23 could be bought freely The rest require connections with the sellers or overpayment or they are rationed. _ Soviets eat half the meat and fruit consumed by the average American, but twice as many potatoes _ Because of losses in distribution and processing, one-quarter of all farm products do n't reach consumers _ Nearly 80 percent of Muscovites buy up items in short supply, even though they do n't really need them at the time, and there is unsatisfied consumer demand in the capital worth the equivalent of $ 14 million to $ 16 billion, a research institute estimates <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> now speaks openly about the failures of perestroika and has increasingly expressed worry over the people's mood. `` The shortage of food creates social tension and generates not merely criticism but actual discontent,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in March. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Maslyukov </PERSON>, the state planning chief, also has spoken of `` mounting social discontent.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his aides admit they failed initially to pay enough attention to the people's welfare and say improving it is now their No. 1 priority. `` All of our productive capacity must be reoriented to produce what the people need: consumer goods,'' the Soviet leader said in May. To that end, some 300 military factories are being converted to civilian production and the 1990 government budget calls for increasing consumer goods output by 12 percent. The Kremlin also is turning to other countries for quick fixes. It plans to use its precious reserves of foreign currency and Western credits to import $ 51.8 billion worth of consumer goods next year. To help Soviet industry gear up to produce such goods on its own, plans call for importing $ 2.6 billion worth of raw materials and light industry equipment. This year, the government brought in 15 million pair of leather shoes, 12 million pair of warm women's boots, 300 million razor blades, 10 million compact cassette players, as well as clothing, soap, detergent and toothpaste. Contracts were signed with foreign companies from <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. An encounter with Ms. <PERSON> Panina </PERSON>, the flower saleswoman, showed the imports are reaching the people. Two large boxes of Danish laundry detergent she had bought sat on the ground next to her flower stand. American-brand toothpaste also has appeared in some <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> stores. But the Kremlin can not afford such costly imports for long, and Western officials say they will not help solve the basic problem: inadequacy of domestic production. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid `` might take the pressures off for a few months,'' one senior Western diplomat said, but later `` the shelves would still be bare.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said the `` socio-economic situation'' must be righted within a year and a half at most, but one of his chief economic advisers, <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON>, says it will take twice that long to end shortages. Politburo member <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> estimates it will take until 1996 to bring Soviets' diet up to nutritional norms. In the meantime, Soviets keep scrounging around. `` You must run around to stores to buy what you need,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Panina </PERSON>. A look of wonderment on her face, she added, `` They say in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> you go to one store and buy all you want.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 3</NOTE>
