<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv03   11-30 0930</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 03,0952</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 3, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senators United Against White House Bid To Control Judgeships</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a display of bipartisanship with a vengeance, <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senators are feuding with the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> over the senatorial prerogative of saying who should be appointed a federal judge back home. The administration is trying to enforce a multiple choice system instead of letting <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> senators pick names for almost automatic nomination to federal district judgeships. That has angered Republicans, gained them <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> allies, and set the lines for a confrontation after <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reconvenes on Jan. 23 unless the dispute can be settled first. `` It is said that marriages are made in heaven, but judgeships are made in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>,'' a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senator declared, applauding a Republican colleague for challenging the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on the matter. Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said Wednesday that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` wants a pool of suitable candidates from which he can choose his nominee,'' and govern the process himself. He said if senators wo n't accept those terms, `` that's a matter between them and the president.'' On this one the lines are institutional, not political. Senators do n't have much in the way of patronage, and they are not about to let go of the judgeships on which they have claimed selection rights for 150 years and more. The case at issue involves the appointment of a federal district court judge for <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>. Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON>, R-Vt., has been trying all year to get <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> of Weybridge nominated to fill the vacancy The dispute erupted into debate just before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adjourned 10 days ago. Because of it, <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON> held up the confirmation of federal judges in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, and said he will block nominations wholesale next year if necessary. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican Conference sided with him, and told President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> that he ought to nominate <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON>' choice. <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON> said district court judgeships have been the prerogative of senators since 1840, a tradition so strong that President <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> once nominated a man he did n't want because a senator insisted, and then sent administration aides to lobby, unsuccessfully, against confirmation. That tradition has been whittled a bit during the past two administrations. <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> had selection panels look at all nominees, and required that there be more women and minority nominees. While he bent the old system, he did not break it. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had a review commission, and his administration required that senators send the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> three names for each vacancy instead of just one. But Republican senators left no doubt about which name counted, and they got their way. <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> changes did n't really interfere with <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> prerogatives. `` What formerly was a formality is now a reality,'' <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON> said. `` It is the policy of this administration that any senator must send at least three names, and it also has been made clear to me personally that they are not restricted to those names to select from.'' Bending to the administration, <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON> did supply two more names, but made clear that <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s was the only one acceptable to him <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON> said the names go to `` a review panel of five bureaucrats somewhere in the bowels of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.'' `` If they, as in my case, decide that that candidate is unacceptable, that is the end of the process,'' he said. That's why he decided to fight, using another <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> prerogative to block other nominees. In <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON> said, a nine-member, bipartisan panel reviews candidates for the federal bench. He said <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> was rated the best of a dozen potential nominees, far ahead of any other, and he insisted the state selection board is better equipped than the administration to choose the best judge for <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> that if he yields on <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, every other senator will be at risk when it comes time to fill a federal court vacancy. Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., agreed with <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON> on the system and on the selection of <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, whom he called the best possible choice He said judgeships should continue to be made in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Del. chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said there's more at stake than an ancient prerogative. `` Unlike five bureaucrats in the White House subjecting nominees to litmus tests or any other tests, the home state senators know better the quality of the people in their states,'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> freshman, has ventured no public guess as to why the administration is making his choice a test case. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, who practices law in <LOCATION> Middlebury </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, was an assistant attorney general when <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON> served as state attorney general. <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON>, an aide to <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, has cited <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s membership in the all-male <PERSON> Ethan </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Club </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> resigned from the club before his name was recommended for the bench. <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> once complained to <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> about the membership of another judicial nominee in an all-male club. The nomination of <PERSON> Vaughn </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> was held up for nearly two years, and finally approved this month. There's not much political logic there. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> also was sponsored by a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> senator, and two <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> administrations stuck with him, Democratic opposition and club affiliations notwithstanding.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mears </PERSON>, vice president and columnist for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, has reported on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and national politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
