<FIRST>s a BC-Disabilities-Buses Adv03   11-30 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Disabilities-Buses, Adv 03,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 3, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Seattle a Leader in Wheelchair Bus Access, But at What Cost?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Bob Carroll and B.J. Carol are different people.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Disabilities Act</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1 of Nov. 29</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prospect of outfitting public buses to accept wheelchairs, as the pending Americans With Disabilities Act would require, troubles many transit officials. They say wheelchair lifts are expensive, unreliable and a nuisance to `` normal'' riders. But in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> system started putting lifts on buses 10 years ago and now has them on 75 percent of its 1,000-bus fleet, it's hard to see what all the fuss is about. This city is a leader in making its bus system accessible to lame, deaf, blind and mentally disabled riders. It even gets fan mail: a wheelchair-bound couple from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> recently wrote to say they honeymooned in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> because they knew they'd be able to get around. `` The difference here was that we planned it to succeed rather than to fail,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>. `` The attitude in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> has been that accessibility is worth the cost.'' The cost to the system is high _ $ 3.89 per trip for wheelchair passengers, compared to $ 2 per regular ride. Taxpayers bear the brunt of it; disabled riders pay just 25 cents per trip, less than half the lowest regular fare of 55 cents. But <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> thinks the price is reasonable. Paralyzed from the waist down by a diving accident 15 years ago, he says the city's wheelchair lifts have opened doors once closed to him and other disabled residents `` It's being told, ` You're part of the system,' versus, ` You're a pain in the neck,''' <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> said one recent afternoon as he waited at a downtown bus stop A bus soon eased to a halt, and other passengers hurried on. Seeing <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>'s wheelchair, the driver pushed a button. With the whine of an electric motor, a metal platform slid out from under the front steps. <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> rolled onto the hydraulic lift, which then rose up and over the steps, settling on the floor inside. As the lift reversed itself and slid back out of sight, <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> wheeled down the aisle and, with the driver's help, strapped his wheelchair into a reserved space. The driver was courteous. Some passengers on the crowded bus had to pull their feet back to let <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> pass, but nobody grumbled, and the whole operation took 45 seconds. When <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> started its program, critics held up the failures of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, which had been plagued by lifts malfunctioning up to 70 percent of the time, uncooperative bus drivers and disabled people afraid to use the system. `` I was told the -LRB- bus drivers' -RRB- union would fight it,'' said <PERSON> B.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Carol </PERSON>, who started <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION>'s program in 1978 and now is a private transportation consultant. `` I was told there would be a huge backlash from non-disabled persons refusing to ride with disabled passengers.'' <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> headed off problems by aggressively marketing its new program. Lift-equipped buses visited nursing homes for practice sessions. Officials asked riders for advice and followed it. They augmented wheelchair-accessible buses with `` para-transit'' vans available on a reservation basis for people too disabled to use buses. Perhaps most importantly, they maintained their equipment. Nationwide, wheelchair lifts break down an average 10 percent of the time, an unacceptable rate for riders depending on the bus to get to work, <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>'s malfunction rate hovers around 1 percent, he said. Even here, disabled passengers are still a tiny minority. They account for about 380 rides a day _ less than 1 percent of the system's total ridership. `` It would be more cost-effective to tell them, ` Go jump in the lake, we're not going to serve you at all,''' said <PERSON> Carol </PERSON>. But that, too, would have a price: `` You can support disabled people in a warehouse situation, or you can get them in the mainstream, with a job, paying taxes,'' <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> said. `` Overall, it's cost-effective to let people work, because that's what they want to do.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> is the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> regional reporter, based in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
