<SECOND>BC-EXP--Nuclear Priest, Adv 04,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 4, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nuclear Test Controller Lives Double Life As Priest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-EXP--Why We Test</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As an Episcopal priest, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> prays that no one will ever use what he helps to produce at his day job. Other priests may lead protests against nuclear weapons; <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> leads the teams that explode those weapons deep underground at the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> Test Site. It's contradictory, being `` the only priest I know who fires nuclear weapons.'' And it forces him almost daily to reconcile his occupation and his calling. `` There are no right or wrong answers,'' he said. `` I would like to be in a situation where there are no nuclear weapons. But I would also like a situation where we maintain the system of freedom and justice we have in our country.'' The 48-year-old deputy manager of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> operations for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is a nuclear veteran, having begun his career in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> on the staff of Adm. <PERSON> Hyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rickover </PERSON>, a force behind nuclear development. He's a newcomer to the clergy, however, having for years put aside his thoughts of becoming a priest. `` The way God works, he just does n't follow the rules at all. With my family, work and other commitments, I thought becoming a priest was something that just could n't happen,'' said the father of two. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, a lifelong <PERSON> Episcopalian </PERSON>, was nominated into the priesthood by the congregation at <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Saints </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> under a canon allowing elevation of parishioners to priests in remote parishes. He was ordained two years ago. The church has not taken a position on continued nuclear testing. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> takes pains to separate his role as a priest from the job in which he has given the final approval to detonate more than 30 nuclear devices. But he also believes his experience in the weapons program has given him insight into the everyday world that is useful in his role as a priest. `` I deal with a lot of real world things here that perhaps the clergy who have been clergy for their whole careers do n't see,'' he said. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> does n't shy away from defending his beliefs on continued nuclear testing and he is often asked to go before anti-nuclear groups and explain the government's position that testing is vital to the nation's security. `` I do n't think in any of these discussions I change anybody's mind or they change mine, but we come away from honest and direct discussions the better for it The best comment I ever got from one anti-nuclear activist was, ` I do n't agree with what you're doing, but I'm glad you're the one doing it.''' `` He's the kind of guy I admire and respect whether he worked for me or was on the other side,'' said <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquilina </PERSON>, manager of the test site. `` I believe he comes across in a very credible way because he's so honest. I've never second-guessed his motives on anything because he's always so honest.'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> goes out of his way not to criticize anti-nuclear protesters who often congregate at the gates of the test site. Many, in fact, are his friends, including the wife of another Episcopal priest in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> and the priest's wife are founding board members and work closely together on a project to build a shelter for homeless women and children in the city. `` We just do n't talk about nuclear weapons when we're working together. She and I have the same ultimate aim. We'd both like not to have nuclear weapons. The difference is how we get there.''
</TEXT>
