<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 04, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Food-Poisoning Toxin Helps Vocal Cord Disorder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Small doses of a toxin that causes food poisoning can help people with a condition that strangles their voices, researchers say. Injections of botulinum into the vocal cords of people with spasmodic dysphonia relax the tightly squeezed cords within days, said Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Tulane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>'s department of otolaryngology and head and neck surgery The only adverse reactions are brief hoarseness and difficulty swallowing, and the toxin does not spread to the rest of the body. Spasmodic dysphonia is uncommon, but reliable estimates are not available of the number of people affected. It seems to worsen with stress and was long thought to be psychosomatic, but evidence has accumulated linking the problem to nerve disorders such as tics and other uncontrollable movements. Injections of botulinum toxin have been used to treat facial tics, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said, so researchers decided to try it against the vocal cord disorder. Work is also being done in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, said Dr. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Jankovic </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Baylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> neurologist. The treatment does not cure the condition. The shots, costing about $ 300 each, must be repeated every few months. The toxin works with the vocal cords for much the same reason it causes food poisoning, <PERSON> Jankovic </PERSON> said. In each case, it binds to the synapse and blocks release of acetylcholine, a chemical that helps transmit nerve impulses. In the case of food poisoning, the nervous system's control over breathing often is disrupted, causing death by respiratory paralysis, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Listening to the Private Lives of Hogs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers are eavesdropping on the most private, intimate moments in the lives of hogs, hoping for hints that will help farmers. `` We're not trying to talk to the animals. What we're doing is listening to the animals and seeing what they have to tell us,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> DeShazer </PERSON>, who has established that hogs make different sounds identifiable with greeting humans, romancing mating partners, hunger, stress and other conditions. In a more subtle distinction, sound - and signal-analysis equipment has helped determine that there is a single peak to a sound wave emitted by a sow during nursing and a double peak to the sound while giving birth `` Even though it's not picked up by hearing, instruments and maybe other animals can pick it up,'' said <PERSON> DeShazer </PERSON>, an agricultural engineering professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nebraska-Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> whose research has drawn on the talents of psychologists, speech clinicians and even dentists. Differentiating hog sounds could have practical applications. Microphones and sound-measuring devices could summon a farmer to help when a sow is giving birth, for example, or could identify sounds inaudible to humans that might be stressful to hogs _ like a squeaking ventilator fan, he said. Such equipment `` allows us to pick up sounds animals make and to analyze those sounds that tell us there's some stress problems or other indicators that need to be taken care of, or that things seem to be all right.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 4</NOTE>
