<HEAD>Architect of Thrift Bailout Said To Be Pick for Fed Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plans to choose <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a chief architect of the administration's bailout bill for the savings and loan industry, to fill a vacancy on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, an administration source said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plans to nominate <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>, an assistant secretary of the treasury, to fill a vacancy on the seven-member board expiring Jan. 31, 1996, said the source, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> acknowledged that <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> is the top candidate for the vacancy, adding, `` We have not made an announcement at this point. It could come at any day, though.'' <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>, 43, a former <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> professor, is a longtime associate of Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and began serving in his current post in October 1988, shortly after <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> became secretary. This year, <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> attended lengthy congressional sessions to write S & amp; L legislation, representing the administration in behind-the-scenes deliberations. Earlier, he was the No. 2 staff person on a presidential task force <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> headed that studied the October 1987 stock market crash. `` His association with <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> has been so close he's going to be viewed as the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s man on the board,'' said economist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> DRI-McGraw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, forecasting firm. `` Any time you get a strong administration type on the board, it gives the administration a little stronger finger on the lever of monetary policy.'' In recent months, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has been somewhat at odds with the administration, which has favored lower interest rates than the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> and has pressed the central bank to be more aggressive in efforts to improve the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit by manipulating the value of the dollar on world currency markets. <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> would be <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s first appointment to the board. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> named the other six members. However, economists warned that previous <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> appointees viewed as administration representatives subsequently took an independent line. `` Vice Chairman -LRB- <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> came over from the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, but he quickly became his own man,'' said economist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a government securities dealer in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>, if nominated and approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, would succeed <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Heller </PERSON>, who resigned from the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> in June to become executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Visa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the credit card company. <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> has little professional background in broad economic and monetary policy-making but is highly regarded as an expert on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> financial markets and the banking system. He received his undergraduate degree from <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and graduate degrees from the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>. He grew up in <LOCATION> Fayetteville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, where his father was president of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, as the nation's central bank, attempts to fight inflation and sustain economic growth by manipulating interest rates. It also regulates the banks that are members of its system and governs the activities of bank holding companies.
