</ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analytical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. `` But if the environment does n't get better it's going to be difficult for anyone in the industry to have better profits.'' <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> is dividing its businesses into four groups _ capital markets, investment and merchant banking, private client and subsidiary activities _ similar to realigmnents by other firms in recent years. <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> will head the subsidiary activities group that will include <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s money management businesses, which have more than $ 95 billion in assets under management, and its <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> division. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuld </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who heads <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s taxable fixed-income division, was seen as replacing <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> as <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>'s second-in-command, although <PERSON> Fuld </PERSON> was not named as <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> president. <PERSON> Fuld </PERSON> was named president of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s capital markets group, which will include the company's worldwide capital markets activities. He also will oversee <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s administrative side. <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> will head the investment and merchant banking group and <PERSON> Hardwick </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> will be president of the private client group, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s brokerage operations. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> is disbanding its chief policy-making committee, the 11-member policy group, but will create a business development committee to `` help identify future directions for the firm.'' <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s net income fell to $ 106 million in the first nine months of this year, down 3 percent from $ 110 million in the same period last year. The firm's woes stem partly from its January 1988 acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> E.F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for close to $ 1 billion and its 1984 merger with <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kuhn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loeb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The latter deal marked a major expansion for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> from retail brokerage into investment banking _ essentially arranging or providing financing for corporate buyouts. Analysts said <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON>'s old business generally has helped the firm in the last two years, but <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s pre-tax profit margin has not approached its pre-merger levels of 15 percent. For the 1989 third quarter, pre-tax profit margin was just over 1 percent, compared with an industry average of about 4 percent. Additionally, analysts said, the <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> buyout saddled <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> with debt and cost the firm more than $ 1 billion in writeoffs. `` Following the <LOCATION> Lehman </LOCATION> acquisition the significant increase in the capital markets business really made them a force, particularly in mergers and acquisitions,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckenfelder </PERSON>, a securities industry analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. But, he said: `` The <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> acquisition created problems because the business did n't really pick up. It dissipated.'' Because of the slowdown, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> this month said it would cut broker commissions by 1 percent to 2 percent in 1990 and lay off up to 800 employees by year's end. That would reduce the firm to 35,700 employees from a peak of 46,000. Also, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> reportedly is considering selling a portion of its <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> stake to an outside investor to provide the firm with more capital. A deal would have to be approved by <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, which owns 13 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>. The capital infusion could help appease <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The Wall Street credit rating agency last month said it was considering lowering its rating on <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s long - and short-term debt because of the firm's exposure to corporate buyout debts and its softening business prospects <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kriz </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> assistant vice president, said Wednesday the credit rating agency had not made a decision on <LOCATION> Shearson </LOCATION>.
