<FIRST>r f PM-FamilyBusiness     11-30 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Business,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publisher Launches Magazine for Family-Owned Businesses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The owner of an automobile dealership may have more in common than he realizes with the couple that runs a few retail stores or the building contractor who owns operations spread over several states. They are all involved in family-run businesses, and are the targets of the publishers of a new magazine called Family Business. The premiere issue of the magazine was recently sent to a charter susbcriber group numbering 100,000. The magazine will be available monthly both at the newstand and by subscription starting in January. In an interview Wednesday, Publisher <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> estimated there are 7 million family-owned businesses in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But he said that despite the introduction of a number of consumer-oriented business magazines over the past several years, he found none that dealt exclusively with issues important to owners of family businesses. Entrepreneur, for instance, contains information on how to get a business started. But <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> said information on how to pass a business along to heirs may be more relevant for a family-run business that has dealt with startup issues generations earlier. `` There has been a resurgence of interest in family businesses,'' <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> said. He said MBA students five years ago would seldom admit it if they intended to go to work for their own family's business, but today are forming clubs where issues affecting such operations are discussed. The takeover wave has made family-run business a more appealing career option, he said. `` Corporate life is not offering the secure niche people thought it was,'' he said. <PERSON> Samir </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Husni </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> journalism professor who publishes an annual guide to new magazines, said it appears that Family Business has found a niche that has not been filled by other magazines. `` It's a good idea but how well they execute the idea remains to be seen,'' he said. He estimates only two of 10 new magazines survive four years. Family Business is designed for the 1.5 million to 2 million family-owned businesses with sales of $ 1 million to $ 100 million, <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> said. The cover story in the first issue deals with a company that is called into to contain oil and toxic waste spills on waterways, and describes how the father who owns the business is learning to trust his children to run it. Another story discusses how healthy family companies base salaries for family members on performance rather than sentiment. Regular features will include an advice column with tips on raising capital, handling tax issues and settling disputes. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nessel </PERSON>, a former editorial executive with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and Psychology Today magazines, is the editor-in-chief of Family Business, which is being published from <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barrington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. Publishing consultant <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Periodical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said new magazines for small business are `` a hot genre'' sustained partly by the need to advertise a proliferation of new products these businesses may find useful, such as computers, fax machines and cellular telephones. Advertisers in the first issue included investment and business consulting companies, financial services concerns and office equipment makers. There were 12 pages of ads in the first 72-page issue. <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> plans to have an editorial-to-advertising ratio of 60 percent to 40 percent. The magazine is owned by <ORGANIZATION> MLR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>, a family-run business based in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> that publishes the professional magazines Mergers & amp; <ORGANIZATION> Acquisitions </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Directors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Boards and offers database services. <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> said MLR is investing several million dollars in launching the magazine and expects that it will take four years for it to become profitable. He declined to be specific on how much MLR was prepared to lose. Subscriptions will cost $ 33.97 for a year and single copies will be sold for $ 3.50 each at the newstand. <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> said he would eventually like to boost circulation to 250,000 to 300,000.
