<FIRST>r f PM-OTC-ShortSellers     11-30 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OTC-Short Sellers,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Hears About Short-Selling Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After two days of testimony on the pros and cons of short-selling by company heads, traders and exchange officials, a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel is slated to hear from federal regulators next week. Market regulation and enforcement officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> are scheduled to testify about the trading strategy next Wednesday. When selling short, an investor tries to take advantage of an anticipated drop in a company's stock price. The investor borrows stock from a broker, hoping to replace it with stock purchased at a lower price. The investor's profit comes from the difference between the price of the borrowed stock and the lower price paid to replace it. Profits from short-selling can be huge, but the risks are great. If the stock's price does n't go down, the investor will have to pay a higher price to replace the borrowed stock. In opening three days of hearings on short-selling Tuesday, Rep. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Ga., said the practice is legitimate and accepted in the market, but the subcommittee was concerned about `` persistent reports of efforts by short-sellers to manipulate stock prices downward through various techniques meant to be harmful to the companies or their shareholders. <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> chairs the commerce, consumer and monetary affairs subcommittee of the House Government Operations Committee. On Wednesday, the head of a nationwide association of companies traded in the over-the-counter market told the panel that tougher federal disclosure laws are needed to curb manipulative practices in short-selling. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Guion </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> OTC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel that a survey conducted by the 800-member organization points out the need for such curbs. Of the 183 companies responding to the survey, 22 percent said they believed their company's stock had been the subject of short-selling by professional short-sellers. <PERSON> Guion </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> should adopt a rule requiring anyone who sells short a number of shares exceeding 5 percent of a company's outstanding stock notify the company, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and the market where the stock is traded within 10 days. In earlier testimony, other witnesses complained that professional short-sellers often break the rules to get a stock to drop quickly so they can take their profit and get out. Their alleged methods include spreading false rumors about a company that it is about to declare bankruptcy or that it is under <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> investigation. `` We find these companies are suffering from the standpoint of survival,'' said <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON>, the subcommittee chairman. <PERSON> Guion </PERSON> said 83 percent of the companies surveyed believe short-sellers should be required to report their short interest positions when they exceed a specified amount of shares. But other witnesses were less enthusiastic about such a requirement. `` It's difficult to say that additional information would not be helpful,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION>, a self-regulatory organization that oversees the over-the-counter market. `` But I really do n't think it would be a significant regulatory tool.''
</TEXT>
