<HEAD>Resources Company Cutting Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a decade of playing the field _ from oilfields to goldfields _ <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Moffett </PERSON> is ready to settle down. <PERSON> Moffett </PERSON>, who assembled an unlikely combination of fertilizer mills, oil and gas wells, sulfur mines, <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> copper pits and Australian gold ore into the natural resources company <ORGANIZATION> Freeport-McMoRan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, will sell up to $ 1.5 billion worth of assets. In an abrupt change in strategy, the company said Wednesday it will prune away many of the operations it bought during the 1980s _ fully a third of the company _ and focus on phosphate fertilizers, metals and oil and gas in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` This is a case of selling peanuts to enjoy the watermelon,'' <PERSON> Moffett </PERSON> said, referring to seven operations ranging from the <ORGANIZATION> Freeport-McMoRan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary to the company's Canadian oil and gas reserves. <PERSON> Moffett </PERSON> hopes to realize $ 1.2 to $ 1.5 billion. One unit already has been sold and two were put on the block earlier this year. Of the proceeds, $ 900 million will be used to support huge mineral discoveries made within the past 18 months. One is the largest known existing sulfur deposit in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, called Main Pass Block 299, situated under 200 feet of water off the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> coast. <ORGANIZATION> Freeport </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 58.3 percent of the deposit, estimates it's worth $ 5.4 billion. The other is the Grasberg deposit on the remote <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> island of <ORGANIZATION> Irian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jaya </ORGANIZATION>. Its 3.9 billion pounds of copper more than double the copper reserves of subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Freeport-McMoRan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Copper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Mixed with the copper are 5.6 million ounces of gold _ more than the twice the 2.5 million ounces of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> reserves the company will unload by selling <ORGANIZATION> Freeport-McMoRan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Because the gold is mined along with copper and silver, its production costs should be substantially less than those of the North American With $ 1.8 billion in debt already on its books and only $ 474 million in equity as of Sept. 30, it was time to decide which assets were most expendable, <PERSON> Moffett </PERSON> said. `` We ca n't be everywhere any more,'' <PERSON> Moffett </PERSON> said. `` We have to find niches where we have a leg up.'' The company plans to use up to $ 600 million of the sale proceeds to cut debt. The assets up for sale generated at least $ 345 million in revenues in 1988, according to <ORGANIZATION> Freeport </ORGANIZATION> financial reports _ 18 percent of the company's total. But <PERSON> Moffett </PERSON> said earnings will remain steady through 1992. The gap will be made up by a combination of the cash from the asset sales, a $ 50 million cut in general and administrative costs and lower operating and interest expenses. After 1992, <PERSON> Moffett </PERSON> said, revenues from <LOCATION> Main </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pass </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Grasberg </PERSON> will begin to gush into the company's coffers. Securities analysts agreed. `` We think it's a good move to streamline operations,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranner </PERSON> of <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, <PERSON> Weil </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Labouisse </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Friedrichs </ORGANIZATION>. `` They had to do something about debt.'' Low resource prices, plus high interest costs, depressed the company's earnings performance this year. Earnings fell from $ 3.35 a share in the first nine months of 1988 to $ 1.75 in the same period this year. Investors appeared only mildly impressed by the plan. <ORGANIZATION> Freeport-McMoRan </ORGANIZATION>, which reached a high of $ 38 a share in April, closed at $ 30.12 -LCB- Wednesday, up 50 cents. <ORGANIZATION> Freeport-McMoRan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the Main Pass sulfur deposit, closed at $ 20.50, up 50 cents, while <ORGANIZATION> Freeport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Copper </ORGANIZATION>, which is developing the Grasberg strike, rose 12.5 cents to $ 20.87 -LCB-.
