 Grain and soybean futures prices were broadly higher this morning on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid indications that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> purchased 2 million to 4 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn overnight. The rumored buying, which was not confirmed, would be the first significant grain export deal in several weeks. It sparked a brisk rally in the grain markets, which have been in a downward trend due to the slack foreign demand. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> bought 8 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn in October for shipment in November and December, and was expected to buy more for January-March shipment. `` The question was when would they step in, and they stepped in overnight,'' said <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Zusel </PERSON>, manager of <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s operations on the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> floor In early trading, wheat futures were unchanged to 1 \ cents higher with the contract for delivery in December at $ 4.07 a bushel; corn futures were 1 -RCB- cents to 4 cents higher with December at $ 2.38 -RCB- a bushel; oats were -RCB- cent to 1 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 1.43 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 3 \ cents to 5 -LCB- cents higher with January at $ 5.84 -RCB- a Livestock futures were mostly higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> while pork-belly futures extended their sharp decline into a third day, reflecting disappointment over the slow pace of the government's purchase of pork bellies for shipment to