<HEAD>Baby Food Maker To Close Canadian Plant By April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Gerber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it will close its <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, plant by April, terminating about 150 jobs. The world's largest baby food maker is consolidating production in its three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plants, in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Smith </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Gerber </ORGANIZATION> Chairman and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. Except for two or three supervisory personnel who may be transferred, employees at the Canadian plant will be dismissed, <ORGANIZATION> Gerber </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poole </PERSON> said. Production is to be transferred to the Fremont plant, with some product lines being moved immediately and some during the coming months, <PERSON> Poole </PERSON> said. Dismissals are not expected to begin until early in 1990, he said. <PERSON> Poole </PERSON> said employees will receive help in finding other jobs as well as a severance package including two weeks' pay per year of service, twice what <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> law requires. Those costs will mean a charge of $ 4.5 million, or 12 cents a share, against earnings for <PERSON> Gerber </PERSON>'s third quarter ending Dec. 31, the company said. That would cut third-quarter earnings projected at 58 cents a share, or about $ 21.8 million, before the change, to 46 cents a share, or $ 17.3 million. Gerber reported earnings of $ 19.1 million, or 48 cents a share, for its 1988 third quarter. For its fiscal year ended March 31, <ORGANIZATION> Gerber </ORGANIZATION> reported profits of $ 81.4 million, or $ 4.13 a share, on sales of $ 1.07 billion. <PERSON> Gerber </PERSON> has about 70 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> baby food market and about 25 percent of the Canadian market. It still will pursue Canadian sales, offering its full U.S.-produced array of 184 products rather than just the 94 produced at the <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> plant, <PERSON> Poole </PERSON> said. He said studies that led to closing the <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> plant were based on conditions prior to the U.S.-Canadian free trade agreement adopted this year, and the plant would have been closed with or without the agreement. In addition to baby food, Gerber markets infant and children's wear under the <PERSON> Gerber </PERSON>, <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and Weather Tamer labels The company employs nearly 15,000 people.
