<TEXT>
 A man was held Thursday on racketeering and extortion charges for an alleged plot to kidnap <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> billionaire <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> and hold him for $ 5 million ransom, authorities said. <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Veleff </PERSON>, 57, of <LOCATION> Germantown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, was arrested by <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents Wednesday after he had driven to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> with an undercover agent he thought was going to help him. The arrest came after <PERSON> Veleff </PERSON> took pictures of City Place, a 33-story office complex built by the Bass family where <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> has his office. <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> <PERSON> Andre </PERSON>, an assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Veleff </PERSON> had never met Bass and had no connection with him. He had made Bass the target of a kidnapping after reading about him in a business magazine, <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> said. Federal authorities had been aware of the alleged plot since May. But <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> said <PERSON> Veleff </PERSON> told the undercover agent he had been planning to abduct Bass for seven years. <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, a lawyer for the Bass family, declined to comment. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fallin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, the agent in charge of the investigation, said <PERSON> Veleff </PERSON> planned to ask for $ 5 million ransom after taking Bass to south <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Veleff, an advertising salesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Memphis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> newspaper for about 20 years, had operated a swimming pool business for about eight years before becoming unemployed. If convicted, <PERSON> Veleff </PERSON> could face a maximum prison term of five years and a fine of up to $ 250,000. <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> said that in addition to the $ 5 million ransom Veleff talked about filming Bass `` in distressing situations'' and seeking an additional $ 20 million after the initial ransom had been delivered by plane to a mountain in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The alleged plot called for a pilot to be informed to drop the money on a specified mountain about 45 miles south of border, <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> said. Bass, 41, has a reported wealth of $ 1.44 billion, according to <ORGANIZATION> Forbes </ORGANIZATION> magazine. His brothers, <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>, 46; <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>, 33; and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>, 44, also are reported billionaires. The Bass family's business interests include oil, gas and various investments.
