<FIRST>r f AM-US-SovietTrade     11-30 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet Trade,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen Urge Bush to Push Trade With Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty-three congressmen urged President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Thursday to give priority in his talks with Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to ending a rule that imposes high <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tariffs on imports from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has power to waive the Jackson-Vanik amendment, a provision in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade law that denies the Soviets the `` most favored nation'' status because of limits on emigration. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> already have the status. `` The Soviet government has come a long way in addressing the concerns we have long expressed,'' the congressmen said in a letter to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as he was leaving for the talks with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. `` Assuming you are assured of continued Soviet progress, it is now time to recognize and reward Soviet progress with a waiver under Jackson-Vanik,'' they said. At the end of August, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had allowed more than 96,000 of its citizens to leave, more than in any entire year for the past two decades. The letter was signed six senators, including Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, and 27 House members. All are Democrats except for six <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members. Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who last June introduced a resolution supporting a waiver once <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> received assurances on free emigration from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The Supreme Soviet is expected to complete action in January on a bill to free emigration. The lower tariffs would only take effect after Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials negotiate a trade accord. It was agreed earlier this month to create working parties that would start work on the agreement, but <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorokin </PERSON>, economic counselor at the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, said on Thursday that they have not yet met. Formal negotiations are expected to start later and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials say they would take several months, after which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would issue the waiver.
