<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was mostly lower in light trading Thursday amid more signs of a slowing economy. Gold prices were mixed. The dollar fell in response to a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report that personal income rose 0.9 percent in October and rumors that purchasing executives in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> believed the economy was weakening, said <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, a currency market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> MMS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Both developments `` did n't contradict the idea that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy continued to slow down,'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said. When the economy slows, financial markets expect the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to nudge interest rates lower. Declining rates make the dollar less attractive, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency tends to fall when yields decline. The dollar also slipped as traders who had taken profits against the West German mark in recent days began to rebuild their positions, <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said. The dollar fell to 1.7815 marks in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> from 1.7875 late Wednesday after dropping earlier in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> to 1.7800 marks from late Wednesday's 1.7825. Volume was light as many traders awaited two economic figures to be released Friday, the government's Index of Leading Indicators and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Purchasing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly assessment of the economy. `` Right now, dollar sentiment is so poor, we really need some strong fundamental data in order for it to rally,'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said. Overseas dealers said the dollar fell sharply late in the day on rumors that <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> was resigning because of his one-time consulting role with the troubled <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Coyne </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the rumors were `` absolutely not true,'' and the denial helped steady the dollar somewhat. There was brief dollar buying early in the day after the assassination of <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrhausen </PERSON>, the overseas traders said. They said the buying focused on the potentially destabilizing effect a new wave of terrorism would have on <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and its economy. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Wednesday's quotes, included: 1.5930 Swiss francs, up from 1.5920; 6.0840 French francs, down from 6.0935; 1,312.25 Italian lire, down from 1,318.75; and 1.16405 Canadian dollars, down from 1.16525 The dollar lost ground against the British pound. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, sterling rose to $ 1.5700 from late Wednesday's $ 1.5678, and in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the pound rose to $ 1.5700 from $ 1.5655. The dollar also fell against the Japanese yen, declining to 142.80 yen in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> from 142.825 late Wednesday. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar fell to 142.90 yen from 143.35 yen, and it was unchanged in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at 143.15 yen. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Wednesday's prices, included: 1.5910 Swiss francs, up from 1.5895; 6.0725 French francs, down from 6.0810; 2.0150 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0100; 1,311.50 Italian lire, down from 1,315.50; 1.1632 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1658. Gold prices rose in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading after falling overseas. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, a troy ounce of gold rose $ 2.10 to $ 411.60 on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> quoted a late bid of $ 410.65 for a troy ounce, up $ 2.95. Gold fell earlier in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 410.60 a troy ounce, down from $ 412.50 late Wednesday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the metal fell to a closing bid of $ 409.50, down from $ 411.70 late Wednesday. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 5.59 to close at a bid $ 405.76. Silver prices also were mixed. Silver rose 6.8 cents to $ 5.668 a troy ounce on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after falling in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 5.64, down from $ 5.65 late Wednesday.
