ecember contract at 50.29 cents a gallon. Corn and soybean futures prices ended mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid indications the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> bought 2 million to 4 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn. After the close, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced sales of 1.4 million metric tons of corn and 150,000 metric tons of soybean meal to the Soviets. Wheat futures settled 2 cents lower to 1 -RCB- cents higher with December at $ 4.07 -LCB- a bushel; corn futures were unchanged to 3 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 2.38 \ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 1.42 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 4 -LCB- cents higher with January at $ 5.82 -RCB- a bushel
