<HEAD>Anheuser-Busch Rolls Out New Non-Alcoholic Brew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that it is increasing the availability of its non-alcoholic beer just in time for the holiday season. `` There are many situations where a non-alcohol malt beverage might be preferred, such as during business lunches or while participating in athletic events,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Merz </PERSON>, group brand director for <PERSON> O'Doul </PERSON>'s Non-Alcoholic Brew. `` And with the holidays just around the corner, it might also be preferred when consumers know they will be driving,'' he said. <PERSON> O'Doul </PERSON>'s has been test-marketed since March in cities in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. It will be made available in December in all or part of 12 other states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest brewery, is one of several breweries that have recently introduced non-alcoholic beers. Milwaukee-based <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, for instance, announced plans in October to offer its Sharp's non-alcoholic brew for sale nationwide by Jan. 1. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Krishock </PERSON>, new products category director for <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, said growth in the non-alcoholic beer market prompted <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> to bring <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>'s out nationwide without test marketing. Annual <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production of non-alcoholic beers is about a million barrels a year, compared with the national beer market of more than 182 million barrels. But the non-alcoholic segment is growing at the rate of 10 percent to 15 percent a year while the overall beer market has been stable, analysts s