per hundred pounds. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices farmers got for raw products rose 1.4 percent in November over the month before, chiefly because of increased prices for strawberries, milk, eggs and celery, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. The increases were partially offset by lower prices for hogs, grapefruit, apples and lemons, the department said. The prices were 2.1 percent higher than last year at this time. That increase came from higher prices for milk, hogs, cattle and eggs, partially offset by lower prices for soybeans, corn and broilers over the year, said the report. Feed grain prices, except oats, increased slightly from October. Wheat, rice and soybeans also showed small gains. Hog prices decreased from October, steers and heifers were up, but prices for cows and calves were down. Looking just at crops, the increase in November was .8 percent over the month before, but 5.1 percent below a year ago. Here's what happened: _ Potatoes averaged $ 6.14 per hundred pounds, up 84 cents from October _ Dry bean prices advanced $ 1.60 to $ 27.60 per hundred pounds _ Commercial vegetable prices were 1.4 percent higher due mainly to the near doubling of celery prices caused by a late harvest and celery shortage _ Onions, carrots and lettuce prices were lower than in October _ Oil bearing crop prices were 1.1 higher than in October, but 21 percent below a year ago Soybeans were $ 5.62 per bushel, up 7 cents from October. Peanuts declined 1.2 cents to 25.5 cents per pound. Cottonseed was at $ 111 a ton, an increase of $ 17 from October. Livestock and poultry was up .6 percent from October and 7.9 percent above November a year ago. `` Compared with October, higher prices for milk, eggs, cattle and turkeys more than offset lower prices for hogs, broilers and calves,'' said the report. Here are the details: _ Milk sold to plants and dealers averaged $ 15.20 per hundred pounds in November, up 50 cents from the month before and $ 1.88 from the year before _ <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> prices increased 2.4 cents per pound over October to 40.9 cents _ Broiler prices averaged 29.8 cents per pound down .8 cents from October _ Market egg prices averaged 72.8 cents per dozen for November, an increase of 8.6 cents from October _ Barrow and gilt prices decreased $ 2.30 per hundred pounds from October to $ 45 while sows decreased $ 3.60 per hundred pounds _ Beef cattle prices in November averaged $ 69.40 per hundred pounds up 70 cents from October, while calf prices decreased 80 cents to $ 87.30 per hundred pounds _ Calf prices decreased 80 cents to $ 87.30 per hundred pounds
