<DATELINE>PALTAKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury found <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> guilty Thursday of dumping raw sewage into <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> waterways in the national rail passenger line's first such criminal trial. The state filed charges after <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> refused to stop dumping raw human wastes from moving trains onto the tracks and into the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rice </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>. The six-member jury deliberated 1 -LCB- hours Thursday before returning a guilty verdict on four counts of commercial littering. <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> contended federal law exempts it from state pollution control laws. The dumping practice, dating back more than a century, has also come under fire in several Western states. `` I'm surprised and disappointed in the verdict,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>'s attorney, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> `` I think it's unfair for the law to send mixed signals.'' <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> would appeal the decision `` just as quick as you're looking at daylight.'' <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> also faced one count of creating or allowing a nuisance to health, but <ORGANIZATION> 7th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> remanded it to <ORGANIZATION> Putnam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, saying that prosecutors failed to prove anyone's health was endangered A trial on that count will be set later. <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> has 20 days to file a motion for a new trial on the littering convictions. Sentencing was set for Jan. 19. <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> could be prohibited from dumping and fined up to $ 5,000 on each count. The charges also carry a possible prison term of five years on each count, though no individual was named in the case. `` We are asking for injunction immediately -LRB- to stop <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> from dumping -RRB-,'' said State Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON>. `` But it's obvious that the judge is not going to act until the sentencing date.'' The federally supported passenger railroad had threatened to suspend service to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, where it serves about 1 million passengers a year, if the state continued pressing its case. However, <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>, assistant general counsel for <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>, said following the verdict that no decision has been made to pull the rail service out of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> earlier had indicated if a guilty verdict were returned: `` I do n't think it will immediately affect rail service in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. I think in the long run it will ultimately lead to the end of the practice of dumping sewage in the waterways throughout the country.'' Many of <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>'s 600 passenger cars dispose of sewage either by dumping directly onto the tracks when toilets are flushed or by spraying the contents of 30-gallon holding tanks when the trains are traveling at least 35 miles per hour. In his closing argument, <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> admitted <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> had dumped human waste on bridges crossing waterways in <LOCATION> Putnam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, but said the practice was allowed under federal law. The company said in a federal court motion in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> that enforcement of the state law would impose undue burdens on <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>, but no hearings were held on the motion and <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> refused to delay trial pending a federal ruling. The defense called <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>'s president and chief executive officer, <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Claytor </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, as their only witness during the week-long trial. <PERSON> Claytor </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> recognized the dumping problem, but that the federally funded rail line could do little until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> appropriated more money for holding tanks or new cars. <PERSON> Claytor </PERSON> estimated it would take about $ 1 million to equip the current cars with the new system or $ 2 million to install it in new cars. The prosecution said <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> could not hide behind the law passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1976 and ignore environmental laws in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> needs to know the state of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> will not allow <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> _ the federal government _ to dump raw sewage in the waters of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> said. `` They -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- are trying to stretch the law to say something it does n't.''
